{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"primaryCategory":"Literature & Poetry","subcategory":"Latin American","audienceTags":["tradition:latinAmerican","theme:wisdom","theme:love","theme:storytelling","audience:morning","audience:inspiration"],"sortPriority":35,"groupingLevels":["author"],"groupingLabels":["Author"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/LatinAmerican_Voices.json","supplementalDataPath":null,"languageCode":"en","displayNameEnglish":"Latin American Voices","script":"Latin","isRTL":false,"transliterationAvailable":false,"contentRating":"general","sourceId":"latinAmericanVoices","displayName":"Latin American Voices","version":"1.0","language":"English","edition":"Wikiquote Verified & Public Domain Sources","type":"quotes","browseOrder":"sequence","itemCount":869,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true},"data":[{"id":"latin-neruda-000001","text":"Debajo de tu piel vive la luna.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000002","text":"Mi amor se nutre de tu amor, amada","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000003","text":"¿Sabes que en las calles no hay nadiey adentro de las casas tampoco?Sólo hay ojos en las ventanas.Si no tienes dònde dormirtoca una puerta y te abrirán,te abrirán hasta cierto puntoy verás que hace frío adentro,que aquella casa está vacía,y no quiere nada contigo,no valen nada tus historias,y si insistes con tu ternurate muerden el perro y el gato.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000004","text":"Y algo golpeaba en mi alma,fiebre o alas perdidas,y me fui haciendo solo,descifrandoaquella quemaduray escribí la primera línea vaga,vaga, sin cuerpo, pura,tonteríapura sabiduríadel que no sabe nada,y vi de prontoel cielodesgranadoy abierto.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000005","text":"Es la hora, amor mío, de apartar esta rosa sombría,cerrar las estrellas, enterrar la ceniza en la tierra:y, en la insurrección de la luz, despertar con los que despertarono seguir en el sueño alcanzando la otra orilla del mar que no tiene otra orilla.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000006","text":"Sólo con una ardiente paciencia conquistaremos la espléndida ciudad que dará luz, justicia y dignidad a todos los hombres. Así la poesía no habrá cantado en vano.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000007","text":"Un pilar soportando consuelosY no me digan nada¿Y bien? ¿Te sana el metaloide pálido?Tengo un miedo terrible de ser un animalíY, si después de tantos palabrasLa cólera que quiebra al hombre en niños","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000008","text":"¿Quién escribe tu nombre con letras de humo entre las estrellas del sur?Ah déjame recordarte cómo eras entonces, cuando aún no existías.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Canción Desesperada (Twenty Love Poems and a Song of Despair) (1924)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000009","text":"Quiero hacer contigo lo que la primavera hace con los cerezos.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Canción Desesperada (Twenty Love Poems and a Song of Despair) (1924)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000010","text":"Me gustas cuando callas porque estás como ausente,y me oyes desde lejos, y mi voz no te toca.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Canción Desesperada (Twenty Love Poems and a Song of Despair) (1924)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000011","text":"Puedo escribir los versos más tristes esta noche.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Canción Desesperada (Twenty Love Poems and a Song of Despair) (1924)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000012","text":"Es tan corto el amor y tan largo el olvido.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Veinte Poemas de Amor y una Canción Desesperada (Twenty Love Poems and a Song of Despair) (1924)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000013","text":"Estoy solo entre materias desvencijadas,la lluvia cae sobre mí, y se me parece,se me parece con su desvarío,solitaria en el mundo muerto,rechazada al caer, y sin forma obstinada.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Residencia en la Tierra (Residence on Earth) (1933)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000014","text":"Enterrado junto al cocotero hallarás más tarde el cuchillo que escodí allí por temor de que me mataras,y ahora repentinamente quisiera oler su acero de cocinaacostumbrado al peso de tu mano y al brillo de tu pie:bajo la humedad de la tierra, entre las sordas raíces,de los lenguajes humanos el pobre sólo sabría tu nombre,y la espesa tierra no comprende tu nombrehecho de impenetrables y substancias divinas.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Residencia en la Tierra (Residence on Earth) (1933)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000015","text":"No quiero para mí tantas desgracias.No quiero continuar de raíz y de tumba,de subterráneo solo, de bodega con muertosateridos, muriéndome de pena.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Residencia en la Tierra (Residence on Earth) (1933)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000016","text":"Si me preguntáis en dónde he estadodebo decir \"Sucede.\"Debo de hablar del suelo que oscurecen las piedras,del río que durando se destruye:no sé sino las cosas que los pájaros pierden,el mar dejado atrás, o mi hermana llorando.¿Por qué tantas regiones, por qué un díase junta con un día? ¿Por qué una negra nochese acumula en la boca? ¿Por qué muertos?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Residencia en la Tierra (Residence on Earth) (1933)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000017","text":"Preguntaréis: ¿Y dónde están las lilas?¿Y la metafísica cubierta de amapolas?¿Y la lluvia que a menudo golpeabasus palabras llenándolasde agujeros y pájaros?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Residencia en la Tierra (Residence on Earth) (1933)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000018","text":"Preguntaréis ¿por qué su poesíano nos habla del sueño, de las hojas,de los grandes volcanes de su país natal?Venid a ver la sangre por las calles,venid a verla sangre por las calles,venid a ver la sangrepor las calles!","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Residencia en la Tierra (Residence on Earth) (1933)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-neruda-000019","text":"Muere lentamente quien no viaja, quien no lee,quien no oye música,quien no encuentra gracia en sí mismo.Muere lentamentequien destruye su amor propio,quien no se deja ayudar...","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000020","text":"Podrán cortar todas las flores, pero no podrán detener la primavera.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000021","text":"Works of Neruda (some translated into English)","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000022","text":"True Stone and Epitaph: the Poetry of Pablo Neruda\" by Gilbert Wesley Purdy. A full length book review/essay which includes a critical biography of Pablo Neruda.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000023","text":"La Sebastiana - one of the homes of Neruda.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000024","text":"Celebrating Chilean Poet Pablo Neruda &ndash; Democracy Now! interviews Martin Espada, poet and professor at the University of Massachusetts Amherst.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000025","text":"Pablo Neruda, Winner of the 1971 Nobel Prize in Literature","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000026","text":"The poet conqueror - A review of Neruda: A Passion for Life by Adam Feinstein in The Guardian","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000027","text":"Red Poppy a non-profit dedicated to furthering Neruda's commitment to humanitarianism and spreading his poetry around the world. Home of the critically acclaimed, bestselling \"The Essential Neruda: Selected Poems\" and the documentary \"Pablo Neruda: The Poet's Calling","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000028","text":"Original poems - It includes some translations and audio files. All poems are sourced","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000029","text":"“Those fields, colored by various grain!”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000030","text":"PART I. The Wild Land I II III IV V","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000031","text":"PART II. Neighboring Fields I II III IV V VI VII VIII IX X XI XII","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000032","text":"PART III. Winter Memories I II","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000033","text":"PART IV. The White Mulberry Tree I II III IV V VI VII VIII","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000034","text":"TO THE MEMORY OF SARAH ORNE JEWETT IN WHOSE BEAUTIFUL AND DELICATE WORK THERE IS THE PERFECTION THAT ENDURES","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000035","text":"One January day, thirty years ago, the little town of Hanover, anchored on a windy Nebraska tableland, was trying not to be blown away.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000036","text":"A mist of fine snowflakes was curling and eddying about the cluster of low drab buildings huddled on the gray prairie, under a gray sky.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000037","text":"The dwelling-houses were set about haphazard on the tough prairie sod; some of them looked as if they had been moved in overnight, and others as if they were straying off by themselves, headed straight for the open plain.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000038","text":"None of them had any appearance of permanence, and the howling wind blew under them as well as over them.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000039","text":"The main street was a deeply rutted road, now frozen hard, which ran from the squat red railway station and the grain “elevator” at the north end of the town to the lumber yard and the horse pond at the south end.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000040","text":"On either side of this road straggled two uneven rows of wooden buildings; the general merchandise stores, the two banks, the drug store, the feed store, the saloon, the post-office.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000041","text":"The board sidewalks were gray with trampled snow, but at two o’clock in the afternoon the shopkeepers, having come back from dinner, were keeping well behind their frosty windows.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000042","text":"The children were all in school, and there was nobody abroad in the streets but a few rough-looking countrymen in coarse overcoats, with their long caps pulled down to their noses.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000043","text":"Some of them had brought their wives to town, and now and then a red or a plaid shawl flashed out of one store into the shelter of another.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000044","text":"At the hitch-bars along the street a few heavy work-horses, harnessed to farm wagons, shivered under their blankets.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000045","text":"About the station everything was quiet, for there would not be another train in until night.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000046","text":"On the sidewalk in front of one of the stores sat a little Swede boy, crying bitterly.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000047","text":"His black cloth coat was much too big for him and made him look like a little old man.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000048","text":"His shrunken brown flannel dress had been washed many times and left a long stretch of stocking between the hem of his skirt and the tops of his clumsy, copper-toed shoes.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000049","text":"His cap was pulled down over his ears; his nose and his chubby cheeks were chapped and red with cold.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000050","text":"He cried quietly, and the few people who hurried by did not notice him.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000051","text":"He was afraid to stop any one, afraid to go into the store and ask for help, so he sat wringing his long sleeves and looking up a telegraph pole beside him, whimpering, “My kitten, oh, my kitten!","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000052","text":"Her will fweeze!” At the top of the pole crouched a shivering gray kitten, mewing faintly and clinging desperately to the wood with her claws.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000053","text":"The boy had been left at the store while his sister went to the doctor’s office, and in her absence a dog had chased his kitten up the pole.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000054","text":"The little creature had never been so high before, and she was too frightened to move.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000055","text":"Her master was sunk in despair.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000056","text":"He was a little country boy, and this village was to him a very strange and perplexing place, where people wore fine clothes and had hard hearts.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000057","text":"He always felt shy and awkward here, and wanted to hide behind things for fear some one might laugh at him.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000058","text":"Just now, he was too unhappy to care who laughed.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000059","text":"At last he seemed to see a ray of hope: his sister was coming, and he got up and ran toward her in his heavy shoes.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000060","text":"His sister was a tall, strong girl, and she walked rapidly and resolutely, as if she knew exactly where she was going and what she was going to do next.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000061","text":"She wore a man’s long ulster (not as if it were an affliction, but as if it were very comfortable and belonged to her; carried it like a young soldier), and a round plush cap, tied down with a thick veil.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000062","text":"She had a serious, thoughtful face, and her clear, deep blue eyes were fixed intently on the distance, without seeming to see anything, as if she were in trouble.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000063","text":"She did not notice the little boy until he pulled her by the coat.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000064","text":"Then she stopped short and stooped down to wipe his wet face.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000065","text":"“Why, Emil! I told you to stay in the store and not to come out. What is the matter with you?”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000066","text":"“My kitten, sister, my kitten! A man put her out, and a dog chased her up there.” His forefinger, projecting from the sleeve of his coat, pointed up to the wretched little creature on the pole.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000067","text":"Didn’t I tell you she’d get us into trouble of some kind, if you brought her?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000068","text":"But there, I ought to have known better myself.” She went to the foot of the pole and held out her arms, crying, “Kitty, kitty, kitty,” but the kitten only mewed and faintly waved its tail.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000069","text":"Alexandra turned away decidedly.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000070","text":"Somebody will have to go up after her.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000071","text":"I saw the Linstrums’ wagon in town.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000072","text":"I’ll go and see if I can find Carl.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000073","text":"Only you must stop crying, or I won’t go a step.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000074","text":"Did you leave it in the store?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000075","text":"Hold still, till I put this on you.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000076","text":"She unwound the brown veil from her head and tied it about his throat.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000077","text":"He took his cigar out of his mouth and held the wet end between the fingers of his woolen glove.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000078","text":"“My God, girl, what a head of hair!” he exclaimed, quite innocently and foolishly.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000079","text":"She stabbed him with a glance of Amazonian fierceness and drew in her lower lip—most unnecessary severity.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000080","text":"It gave the little clothing drummer such a start that he actually let his cigar fall to the sidewalk and went off weakly in the teeth of the wind to the saloon.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000081","text":"His hand was still unsteady when he took his glass from the bartender.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000082","text":"His feeble flirtatious instincts had been crushed before, but never so mercilessly.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000083","text":"He felt cheap and ill-used, as if some one had taken advantage of him.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000084","text":"When a drummer had been knocking about in little drab towns and crawling across the wintry country in dirty smoking-cars, was he to be blamed if, when he chanced upon a fine human creature, he suddenly wished himself more of a man?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000085","text":"While the little drummer was drinking to recover his nerve, Alexandra hurried to the drug store as the most likely place to find Carl Linstrum.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000086","text":"There he was, turning over a portfolio of chromo “studies” which the druggist sold to the Hanover women who did china-painting.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000087","text":"Alexandra explained her predicament, and the boy followed her to the corner, where Emil still sat by the pole.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000088","text":"“I’ll have to go up after her, Alexandra.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000089","text":"I think at the depot they have some spikes I can strap on my feet.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000090","text":"Wait a minute.” Carl thrust his hands into his pockets, lowered his head, and darted up the street against the north wind.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000091","text":"He was a tall boy of fifteen, slight and narrow-chested.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000092","text":"When he came back with the spikes, Alexandra asked him what he had done with his overcoat.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000093","text":"I couldn’t climb in it, anyhow.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000094","text":"Catch me if I fall, Emil,” he called back as he began his ascent.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000095","text":"Alexandra watched him anxiously; the cold was bitter enough on the ground.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000096","text":"The kitten would not budge an inch.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000097","text":"Carl had to go to the very top of the pole, and then had some difficulty in tearing her from her hold.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000098","text":"When he reached the ground, he handed the cat to her tearful little master.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000099","text":"“Now go into the store with her, Emil, and get warm.” He opened the door for the child.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000100","text":"Why can’t I drive for you as far as our place?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000101","text":"It’s getting colder every minute.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000102","text":"But he says father can’t get better; can’t get well.” The girl’s lip trembled.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000103","text":"She looked fixedly up the bleak street as if she were gathering her strength to face something, as if she were trying with all her might to grasp a situation which, no matter how painful, must be met and dealt with somehow.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000104","text":"The wind flapped the skirts of her heavy coat about her.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000105","text":"Carl did not say anything, but she felt his sympathy.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000106","text":"He was a thin, frail boy, with brooding dark eyes, very quiet in all his movements.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000107","text":"There was a delicate pallor in his thin face, and his mouth was too sensitive for a boy’s.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000108","text":"The lips had already a little curl of bitterness and skepticism.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000109","text":"The two friends stood for a few moments on the windy street corner, not speaking a word, as two travelers, who have lost their way, sometimes stand and admit their perplexity in silence.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000110","text":"When Carl turned away he said, “I’ll see to your team.” Alexandra went into the store to have her purchases packed in the egg-boxes, and to get warm before she set out on her long cold drive.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000111","text":"When she looked for Emil, she found him sitting on a step of the staircase that led up to the clothing and carpet department.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000112","text":"He was playing with a little Bohemian girl, Marie Tovesky, who was tying her handkerchief over the kitten’s head for a bonnet.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000113","text":"Marie was a stranger in the country, having come from Omaha with her mother to visit her uncle, Joe Tovesky.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000114","text":"She was a dark child, with brown curly hair, like a brunette doll’s, a coaxing little red mouth, and round, yellow-brown eyes.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000115","text":"Every one noticed her eyes; the brown iris had golden glints that made them look like gold-stone, or, in softer lights, like that Colorado mineral called tiger-eye.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000116","text":"The country children thereabouts wore their dresses to their shoe-tops, but this city child was dressed in what was then called the “Kate Greenaway” manner, and her red cashmere frock, gathered full from the yoke, came almost to the floor.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000117","text":"This, with her poke bonnet, gave her the look of a quaint little woman.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000118","text":"She had a white fur tippet about her neck and made no fussy objections when Emil fingered it admiringly.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000119","text":"Alexandra had not the heart to take him away from so pretty a playfellow, and she let them tease the kitten together until Joe Tovesky came in noisily and picked up his little niece, setting her on his shoulder for every one to see.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000120","text":"His children were all boys, and he adored this little creature.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000121","text":"His cronies formed a circle about him, admiring and teasing the little girl, who took their jokes with great good nature.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000122","text":"They were all delighted with her, for they seldom saw so pretty and carefully nurtured a child.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000123","text":"They told her that she must choose one of them for a sweetheart, and each began pressing his suit and offering her bribes; candy, and little pigs, and spotted calves.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000124","text":"She looked archly into the big, brown, mustached faces, smelling of spirits and tobacco, then she ran her tiny forefinger delicately over Joe’s bristly chin and said, “Here is my sweetheart.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000125","text":"The Bohemians roared with laughter, and Marie’s uncle hugged her until she cried, “Please don’t, Uncle Joe!","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000126","text":"You hurt me.” Each of Joe’s friends gave her a bag of candy, and she kissed them all around, though she did not like country candy very well.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000127","text":"Perhaps that was why she bethought herself of Emil.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000128","text":"The farm people were making preparations to start for home.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000129","text":"The women were checking over their groceries and pinning their big red shawls about their heads.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000130","text":"The men were buying tobacco and candy with what money they had left, were showing each other new boots and gloves and blue flannel shirts.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000131","text":"Three big Bohemians were drinking raw alcohol, tinctured with oil of cinnamon.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000132","text":"This was said to fortify one effectually against the cold, and they smacked their lips after each pull at the flask.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000133","text":"Their volubility drowned every other noise in the place, and the overheated store sounded of their spirited language as it reeked of pipe smoke, damp woolens, and kerosene.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000134","text":"Carl came in, wearing his overcoat and carrying a wooden box with a brass handle.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000135","text":"“Come,” he said, “I’ve fed and watered your team, and the wagon is ready.” He carried Emil out and tucked him down in the straw in the wagonbox.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000136","text":"The heat had made the little boy sleepy, but he still clung to his kitten.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000137","text":"“You were awful good to climb so high and get my kitten, Carl. When I get big I’ll climb and get little boys’ kittens for them,” he murmured drowsily. Before the horses were over the first hill, Emil and his cat were both fast asleep.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000138","text":"Although it was only four o’clock, the winter day was fading.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000139","text":"The road led southwest, toward the streak of pale, watery light that glimmered in the leaden sky.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000140","text":"The little town behind them had vanished as if it had never been, had fallen behind the swell of the prairie, and the stern frozen country received them into its bosom.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000141","text":"The homesteads were few and far apart; here and there a windmill gaunt against the sky, a sod house crouching in a hollow.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000142","text":"But the great fact was the land itself, which seemed to overwhelm the little beginnings of human society that struggled in its sombre wastes.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000143","text":"The wagon jolted along over the frozen road. The two friends had less to say to each other than usual, as if the cold had somehow penetrated to their hearts.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000144","text":"“Did Lou and Oscar go to the Blue to cut wood to-day?” Carl asked.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000145","text":"I’m almost sorry I let them go, it’s turned so cold.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000146","text":"But mother frets if the wood gets low.” She stopped and put her hand to her forehead, brushing back her hair.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000147","text":"“I don’t know what is to become of us, Carl, if father has to die.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000148","text":"I don’t dare to think about it.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000149","text":"I wish we could all go with him and let the grass grow back over everything.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000150","text":"Just ahead of them was the Norwegian graveyard, where the grass had, indeed, grown back over everything, shaggy and red, hiding even the wire fence.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000151","text":"Carl realized that he was not a very helpful companion, but there was nothing he could say.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000152","text":"“Of course,” Alexandra went on, steadying her voice a little, “the boys are strong and work hard, but we’ve always depended so on father that I don’t see how we can go ahead. I almost feel as if there were nothing to go ahead for.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000153","text":"He lies and counts on his fingers all day.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000154","text":"I think he is trying to count up what he is leaving for us.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000155","text":"It’s a comfort to him that my chickens are laying right on through the cold weather and bringing in a little money.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000156","text":"I wish we could keep his mind off such things, but I don’t have much time to be with him now.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000157","text":"“I wonder if he’d like to have me bring my magic lantern over some evening?”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000158","text":"Alexandra turned her face toward him. “Oh, Carl! Have you got it?”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000159","text":"“Yes. It’s back there in the straw. Didn’t you notice the box I was carrying? I tried it all morning in the drug-store cellar, and it worked ever so well, makes fine big pictures.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000160","text":"“Oh, hunting pictures in Germany, and Robinson Crusoe and funny pictures about cannibals. I’m going to paint some slides for it on glass, out of the Hans Andersen book.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000161","text":"Alexandra seemed actually cheered.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000162","text":"There is often a good deal of the child left in people who have had to grow up too soon.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000163","text":"I can hardly wait to see it, and I’m sure it will please father.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000164","text":"He likes the calendars I get him in town.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000165","text":"You must leave me here, mustn’t you?","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000166","text":"It’s been nice to have company.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000167","text":"Carl stopped the horses and looked dubiously up at the black sky. “It’s pretty dark. Of course the horses will take you home, but I think I’d better light your lantern, in case you should need it.”","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000168","text":"He gave her the reins and climbed back into the wagon-box, where he crouched down and made a tent of his overcoat.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000169","text":"After a dozen trials he succeeded in lighting the lantern, which he placed in front of Alexandra, half covering it with a blanket so that the light would not shine in her eyes.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000170","text":"“Now, wait until I find my box.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000171","text":"Try not to worry.” Carl sprang to the ground and ran off across the fields toward the Linstrum homestead.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000172","text":"“Hoo, hoo-o-o-o!” he called back as he disappeared over a ridge and dropped into a sand gully.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000173","text":"The wind answered him like an echo, “Hoo, hoo-o-o-o-o-o!” Alexandra drove off alone.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000174","text":"The rattle of her wagon was lost in the howling of the wind, but her lantern, held firmly between her feet, made a moving point of light along the highway, going deeper and deeper into the dark country.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000175","text":"On one of the ridges of that wintry waste stood the low log house in which John Bergson was dying.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000176","text":"This creek gave a sort of identity to the farms that bordered upon it.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000177","text":"Of all the bewildering things about a new country, the absence of human landmarks is one of the most depressing and disheartening.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000178","text":"The houses on the Divide were small and were usually tucked away in low places; you did not see them until you came directly upon them.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000179","text":"Most of them were built of the sod itself, and were only the unescapable ground in another form.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000180","text":"The roads were but faint tracks in the grass, and the fields were scarcely noticeable.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000181","text":"The record of the plow was insignificant, like the feeble scratches on stone left by prehistoric races, so indeterminate that they may, after all, be only the markings of glaciers, and not a record of human strivings.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000182","text":"In eleven long years John Bergson had made but little impression upon the wild land he had come to tame.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000183","text":"It was still a wild thing that had its ugly moods; and no one knew when they were likely to come, or why.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000184","text":"Its Genius was unfriendly to man.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000185","text":"The sick man was feeling this as he lay looking out of the window, after the doctor had left him, on the day following Alexandra’s trip to town.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000186","text":"There it lay outside his door, the same land, the same lead-colored miles.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000187","text":"He knew every ridge and draw and gully between him and the horizon.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000188","text":"To the south, his plowed fields; to the east, the sod stables, the cattle corral, the pond,—and then the grass.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000189","text":"Bergson went over in his mind the things that had held him back.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000190","text":"One winter his cattle had perished in a blizzard.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000191","text":"The next summer one of his plow horses broke its leg in a prairiedog hole and had to be shot.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000192","text":"Another summer he lost his hogs from cholera, and a valuable stallion died from a rattlesnake bite.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000193","text":"Time and again his crops had failed.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000194","text":"He had lost two children, boys, that came between Lou and Emil, and there had been the cost of sickness and death.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000195","text":"Now, when he had at last struggled out of debt, he was going to die himself.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000196","text":"He was only forty-six, and had, of course, counted upon more time.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000197","text":"Bergson had spent his first five years on the Divide getting into debt, and the last six getting out.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000198","text":"He had paid off his mortgages and had ended pretty much where he began, with the land.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000199","text":"So far John had not attempted to cultivate the second half-section, but used it for pasture land, and one of his sons rode herd there in open weather.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000200","text":"John Bergson had the Old-World belief that land, in itself, is desirable.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000201","text":"It was like a horse that no one knows how to break to harness, that runs wild and kicks things to pieces.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000202","text":"He had an idea that no one understood how to farm it properly, and this he often discussed with Alexandra.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000203","text":"Their neighbors, certainly, knew even less about farming than he did.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000204","text":"Many of them had never worked on a farm until they took up their homesteads.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000205","text":"They had been _handwerkers_ at home; tailors, locksmiths, joiners, cigar-makers, etc.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000206","text":"Bergson himself had worked in a shipyard.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000207","text":"For weeks, John Bergson had been thinking about these things.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000208","text":"His bed stood in the sitting-room, next to the kitchen.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000209","text":"Through the day, while the baking and washing and ironing were going on, the father lay and looked up at the roof beams that he himself had hewn, or out at the cattle in the corral.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000210","text":"He counted the cattle over and over.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000211","text":"It diverted him to speculate as to how much weight each of the steers would probably put on by spring.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000212","text":"He often called his daughter in to talk to her about this.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000213","text":"Before Alexandra was twelve years old she had begun to be a help to him, and as she grew older he had come to depend more and more upon her resourcefulness and good judgment.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000214","text":"His boys were willing enough to work, but when he talked with them they usually irritated him.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000215","text":"It was Alexandra who read the papers and followed the markets, and who learned by the mistakes of their neighbors.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000216","text":"It was Alexandra who could always tell about what it had cost to fatten each steer, and who could guess the weight of a hog before it went on the scales closer than John Bergson himself.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000217","text":"Lou and Oscar were industrious, but he could never teach them to use their heads about their work.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000218","text":"Alexandra, her father often said to himself, was like her grandfather; which was his way of saying that she was intelligent.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000219","text":"John Bergson’s father had been a shipbuilder, a man of considerable force and of some fortune.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000220","text":"Late in life he married a second time, a Stockholm woman of questionable character, much younger than he, who goaded him into every sort of extravagance.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000221","text":"On the shipbuilder’s part, this marriage was an infatuation, the despairing folly of a powerful man who cannot bear to grow old.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000222","text":"In a few years his unprincipled wife warped the probity of a lifetime.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000223","text":"He speculated, lost his own fortune and funds entrusted to him by poor seafaring men, and died disgraced, leaving his children nothing.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000224","text":"But when all was said, he had come up from the sea himself, had built up a proud little business with no capital but his own skill and foresight, and had proved himself a man.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000225","text":"In his daughter, John Bergson recognized the strength of will, and the simple direct way of thinking things out, that had characterized his father in his better days.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000226","text":"He would much rather, of course, have seen this likeness in one of his sons, but it was not a question of choice.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000227","text":"As he lay there day after day he had to accept the situation as it was, and to be thankful that there was one among his children to whom he could entrust the future of his family and the possibilities of his hard-won land.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-neruda-000228","text":"The winter twilight was fading.","author":"Pablo Neruda","source":"Gutenberg Poetry","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-ggm-000001","text":"...a lie is more comfortable than doubt, more useful than love, more lasting than truth ...","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-ggm-000002","text":"Santiago Nasar had often told me that the smell of closed-in flowers had an immediate relation to death for him.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-ggm-000003","text":"It always amuses me that the biggest praise for my work comes for the imagination, while the truth is that there's not a single line in all my work that does not have a basis in reality. The problem is that Caribbean reality resembles the wildest imagination.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000004","text":"In the end all books are written for your friends. The problem after writing One Hundred Years of Solitude was that now I no longer know whom of the millions of readers I am writing for; this upsets and inhibits me. It's like a million eyes are looking at you and you don't really know what they think.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000005","text":"Interviewer: You describe seemingly fantastic events in such minute detail that it gives them their own reality. Is this something you have picked up from journalism? García Márquez: That's a journalistic trick which you can also apply to literature. If you say that there are elephants flying in the sky, people are not going to believe you. But if you say that there are four hundred and twenty-five elephants in the sky, people will probably believe you.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000006","text":"Ultimately, literature is nothing but carpentry.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000007","text":"I would like for my books to have been recognized posthumously, at least in capitalist countries, where they turn you into a kind of merchandise.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000008","text":"I can't think of any one film that improved on a good novel, but I can think of many good films that came from very bad novels.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000009","text":"I was asked the other day if I would be interested in the Nobel Prize, but I think that for me it would be an absolute catastrophe. I would certainly be interested in deserving it, but to receive it would be terrible. It would just complicate even more the problems of fame. The only thing I really regret in life is not having a daughter.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"The Paris Review interview (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000010","text":"Life is not what one lived, but what one remembers and how one remembers it in order to recount it.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000011","text":"Before adolescence, memory is more interested in the future than the past...","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000012","text":"Nostalgia, as always, had wiped away bad memories and magnified the good ones.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000013","text":"Now you don't have to say yes because your heart is saying it for you.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000014","text":"Children's lies are signs of great talent.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000015","text":"But I believe without any doubt at all that our greatest good fortune was that even in the most extreme difficulties we might lose our patience but never our sense of humor.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000016","text":"It was impossible to conceive of two creatures so different who got along so well and loved each other so much.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000017","text":"From the time they turned one they were tossed from the balconies of the kitchens, first with life preserves so they would lose their fear of the water, and then without life preservers so they would lose their respect for death.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000018","text":"There are no two men in this world more similar than you and him,\" she told me. \"And that's the worst thing for having a conversation.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000019","text":"… no sooner had you done something than someone else appeared who threatened to do it better.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000020","text":"… nothing was easy, least of all surviving Sunday afternoons without love.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000021","text":"… my unhealthy timidity might be a great obstacle to me in my life.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000022","text":"Because for you, quitting smoking would be like killing someone you love.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000023","text":"Until I discovered the miracle that all things that sound are music, including dishes and silverware in the dishwasher, as long as they fulfill the illusion of showing us where life is heading.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000024","text":"I couldn't tell you because even I don't know who I am yet.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000025","text":"… for an instant I thought about stopping the cab to say goodbye, but I preferred not to defy again a destiny as uncertain and persistent as mine.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Living to Tell the Tale (2002)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-ggm-000026","text":"Gabriel García Márquez at Nobelprize.org","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-ggm-000027","text":"Interview with Gabriel García Márquez (1998)","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-ggm-000028","text":"Gabo – The Creation of Gabriel García Márquez. Documentary, Germany, 2015, 90 min.","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-ggm-000029","text":"Love in the time of cholera : contains description of the wreck of the San José at Cartagena de Indias","author":"Gabriel García Márquez","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:magic-realism","theme:storytelling","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000001","text":"If the pages of this book contain some successful verse, the reader must excuse me the discourtesy of having usurped it first. Our nothingness differs little; it is a trivial and chance circumstance that you should be the reader of these exercises and I their author.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000002","text":"Wilde was not a great poet nor a consummate prose writer. He was a very astute Irishman who encompassed in epigrams an esthetic credo which others before him scattered in the space of long pages. He was an enfant terrible.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000003","text":"That one individual should awaken in another memories that belong to still a third is an obvious paradox.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000004","text":"Reading … is an activity subsequent to writing: more resigned, more civil, more intellectual.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000005","text":"The vast ineptitude of his pretense would be a convincing proof that this was no fraud.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000006","text":"Mir Bahadur Ali is, as we have seen, incapable of evading the most vulgar of art's temptations: that of being a genius.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000007","text":"Your unforgivable sins do not allow you to see my splendor.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000008","text":"The earth we inhabit is an error, an incompetent parody. Mirrors and paternity are abominable because they multiply and affirm it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000009","text":"The universe (which others call the Library) is composed of an indefinite and perhaps infinite number of hexagonal galleries, with vast air shafts between, surrounded by very low railings.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000010","text":"There is no combination of characters one can make — dhcmrlchtdj, for example — that the divine Library has not foreseen and that in one or more of its secret tongues does not hide a terrible significance. There is no syllable one can speak that is not filled with tenderness and terror, that is not, in one of those languages, the mighty name of a god.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000011","text":"I know of one semibarbarous zone whose librarians repudiate the \"vain and superstitious habit\" of trying to find sense in books, equating such a quest with attempting to find meaning in dreams or in the chaotic lines on the palms of one's hand.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000012","text":"Que el cielo exista, aunque mi lugar sea el infierno.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000013","text":"El original es infiel a la traducción.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000014","text":"I saw the delicate bone structure of a hand; I saw the survivors of a battle sending out post cards. . . I saw the oblique shadow of some ferns on the floor of a hot-house; I saw tigers, emboli, bison, ground swells and armies; I saw all the ants in the world.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000015","text":"Dictatorships foster oppression, dictatorships foster servitude, dictatorships foster cruelty; more abominable is the fact that they foster idiocy.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000016","text":"There is nothing very remarkable about being immortal; with the exception of mankind, all creatures are immortal, for they know nothing of death. What is divine, terrible, and incomprehensible is to know oneself immortal.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000017","text":"There are no moral or intellectual merits. Homer composed the Odyssey; if we postulate an infinite period of time, with infinite circumstances and changes, the impossible thing is not to compose the Odyssey, at least once.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000018","text":"No one is anyone, one single immortal man is all men. Like Cornelius Agrippa, I am god, I am hero, I am philosopher, I am demon and I am world, which is a tedious way of saying that I do not exist.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000019","text":"Any life, however long and complicated it may be, actually consists of a single moment — the moment when a man knows forever more who he is.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000020","text":"Besides, time, which despoils castles, enriches verses . . . Time broadens the scope of verses and I know of some which, like music, are everything for all men.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000021","text":"There's no need to build a labyrinth when the entire universe is one.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000022","text":"The minotaur more than justifies the existence of the labyrinth.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000023","text":"His many years had reduced and polished him the way water smooths and polishes a stone or generations of men polish a proverb.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000024","text":"I would define the baroque as that style that deliberately exhausts (or tries to exhaust) its own possibilities, and that borders on self-caricature. [...] The baroque is the final stage in all art, when art flaunts and squanders its resources.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000025","text":"To die for a religion is easier than to live it absolutely.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000026","text":"Villari took no notice of them because the idea of a coincidence between art and reality was alien to him. Unlike people who read novels, he never saw himself as a character in a work of art.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000027","text":"Years of solitude had taught him that, in one's memory, all days tend to be the same, but that there is not a day, not even in jail or in the hospital, which does not bring surprises, which is not a translucent network of minimal surprises.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000028","text":"Every novel is an ideal plane inserted into the realm of reality.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000029","text":"The heresies we should fear are those which can be confused with orthodoxy.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000030","text":"Like all those possessing a library, Aurelian was aware that he was guilty of not knowing his in its entirety.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000031","text":"Do you want to see what human eyes have never seen? Look at the moon. Do you want to hear what ears have never heard? Listen to the bird's cry. Do you want to touch what hands have never touched? Touch the earth. Verily I say that God is about to create the world.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000032","text":"Arrasado el jardín, profanados los cálices y las aras, entraron a caballo los hunos en la biblioteca monástica y rompieron los libros incomprensibles y los vituperaron y los quemaron, acaso temerosos de que las letras encubrieran blasfemias contra su dios, que era una cimitarra de hierro.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000033","text":"Writing is nothing more than a guided dream.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000034","text":"He sospechado alguna vez que la única cosa sin misterio es la felicidad, porque se justifica por sí sola.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000035","text":"My advanced age has taught me the resignation of being Borges.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000036","text":"Time can't be measured in days the way money is measured in pesos and centavos, because all pesos are equal, while every day, perhaps every hour, is different.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000037","text":"The poverty of yesterday was less squalid than the poverty we purchase with our industry today. Fortunes were smaller then as well.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000038","text":"We all think that fate has dealt us a wretched sort of lot in life, and that others must be better. [...] I presume that in the heaven of the Blessèd there are those who believe that the advantages of that locale are much exaggerated by theologists, who have never been there themselves.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000039","text":"When one confesses to an act, one ceases to be an actor in it and becomes its witness, becomes a man that observes and narrates it and no longer the man that performed it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000040","text":"Being with you and not being with you is the only way I have to measure time.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000041","text":"El hecho ocurrió en el mes de febrero de 1969, al norte de Boston, en Cambridge. No lo escribí inmediatamente porque mi primer propósito fue olvidarlo, para no perder la razón.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000042","text":"I do believe that my country is now joyfully emerging from the swamp. I believe that we deserve to leave the swamp we have been in. And we are leaving it thanks to the work of the Sword. Here, you have already emerged from the swamp. And so Chile, this region, this country, is both a long country and an honorable Sword.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000043","text":"Ser conservador es una forma de ser escéptico.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000044","text":"Truly fine poetry must be read aloud. A good poem does not allow itself to be read in a low voice or silently. If we can read it silently, it is not a valid poem: a poem demands pronunciation. Poetry always remembers that it was an oral art before it was a written art. It remembers that it was first song.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000045","text":"Films are even stranger, for what we are seeing are not disguised people but photographs of disguised people, and yet we believe them while the film is being shown.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000046","text":"The fact is that poetry is not the books in the library . . . Poetry is the encounter of the reader with the book, the discovery of the book.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000047","text":"The aesthetic event is something as evident, as immediate, as indefinable as love, the taste of fruit, of water. We feel poetry as we feel the closeness of a woman, or as we feel a mountain or a bay. If we feel it immediately, why dilute it with other words, which no doubt will be weaker than our feelings?","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000048","text":"There are people who barely feel poetry, and they are generally dedicated to teaching it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000049","text":"La duda es uno de los nombres de la inteligencia.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000050","text":"As I think of the many myths, there is one that is very harmful, and that is the myth of countries. I mean, why should I think of myself as being an Argentine, and not a Chilean, and not an Uruguayan. I don't know really. All of those myths that we impose on ourselves — and they make for hatred, for war, for enmity — are very harmful. Well, I suppose in the long run, governments and countries will die out and we'll be just, well, cosmopolitans.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000051","text":"No estoy seguro de que yo exista, en realidad. Soy todos los autores que he leído, toda la gente que he conocido, todas las mujeres que he amado. Todas las ciudades que he visitado, todos mis antepasados...","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000052","text":"He cometido el peor pecado que uno puede cometer. No he sido feliz.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000053","text":"The man who acquires an encyclopedia does not thereby acquire every line, every paragraph, every page, and every illustration; he acquires the possibility of becoming familiar with one and another of those things.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000054","text":"The Falklands thing was a fight between two bald men over a comb.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000055","text":"A writer — and, I believe, generally all persons — must think that whatever happens to him or her is a resource. All things have been given to us for a purpose, and an artist must feel this more intensely. All that happens to us, including our humiliations, our misfortunes, our embarrassments, all is given to us as raw material, as clay, so that we may shape our art.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000056","text":"¿De qué otra forma se puede amenazar que no sea de muerte? Lo interesante, lo original, sería que alguien lo amenace a uno con la inmortalidad.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000057","text":"Time carries him as the river carries A leaf in the downstream water. No matter. The enchanted one insists And shapes God with delicate geometry. Since his illness, since his birth, He goes on constructing God with the word. The mightiest love was granted him Love that does not expect to be loved.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000058","text":"Reality is not always probable, or likely. But if you're writing a story, you have to make it as plausible as you can, because if not, the reader's imagination will reject it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000059","text":"En mi juventud probé la mescalina y la cocaína pero enseguida me pasé a los pastillas de menta que me parecieron más estimulantes. Si las drogas producen el mismo efecto que el alcohol, no me interesan. Un borracho es evidentemente ridículo. He estado borracho algunas veces y lo recuerdo como una experiencia muy desagradable para los demás y para mí.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000060","text":"I will pause to consider this eternity from which the subsequent ones derive.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000061","text":"El infierno y el paraíso me parecen desproporcionados. Los actos de los hombres no merecen tanto.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000062","text":"Censorship is the mother of metaphor.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000063","text":"Life and death have been lacking in my life.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000064","text":"Imprecision is tolerable and verisimilar in literature, because we always tend towards it in life.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000065","text":"The exercise of letters is sometimes linked to the ambition to construct an absolute book, a book of books that includes the others like a Platonic archetype, an object whose virtues are not diminished by the passage of time.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000066","text":"Art always opts for the individual, the concrete; art is not Platonic.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000067","text":"It is known that Whistler when asked how long it took him to paint one of his \"nocturnes\" answered: \"All of my life.\" With the same rigor he could have said that all of the centuries that preceded the moment when he painted were necessary. From that correct application of the law of causality it follows that the slightest event presupposes the inconceivable universe and, conversely, that the universe needs even the slightest of events.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000068","text":"We (the indivisible divinity that works in us) have dreamed the world. We have dreamed it resistant, mysterious, visible, ubiquitous in space and firm in time, but we have allowed slight, and eternal, bits of the irrational to form part of its architecture so as to know that it is false.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000069","text":"Hay un concepto que es el corruptor y el desatinador de los otros. No hablo del mal cuyo limitado imperio es la ética; hablo del infinito.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000070","text":"He transforms all concepts into incommunicable, solidified objects. To refute him is to become contaminated with unreality.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000071","text":"It is venturesome to think that a coordination of words (philosophies are nothing more than that) can resemble the universe very much. It is also venturesome to think that of all these illustrious coordinations, one of them — at least in an infinitesimal way — does not resemble the universe a bit more than the others.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000072","text":"The central problem of novel-writing is causality.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Discussion (1932)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000073","text":"I owe the discovery of Uqbar to the conjunction of a mirror and an encyclopedia.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000074","text":"One of the heresiarchs of Uqbar had stated that mirrors and copulation are abominable, since they both multiply the numbers of man.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000075","text":"Para uno de esos gnosticos, el visible universo era una ilusion o (mas precisamente) un sofisma. Los espejos y la paternidad son abominables porque lo multiplican y lo divulgan.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000076","text":"In life, he suffered from a sense of unreality, as do many Englishmen.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000077","text":"One thinker no less brilliant than the heresiarch himself, but in the orthodox tradition, advanced a most daring hypothesis. This felicitous supposition declared that there is only one Individual, and that this indivisible Individual is every one of the separate beings in the universe, and that these beings are the instruments and masks of divinity itself.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000078","text":"The geometry of Tlön comprises two somewhat different disciplines: the visual and the tactile. The latter corresponds to our own geometry and is subordinated to the first.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000079","text":"It is no exaggeration to state that the classic culture of Tlön comprises only one discipline: psychology. All others are subordinated to it. I have said that the men of this planet conceive the universe as a series of mental processes which do not develop in space but successively in time.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000080","text":"The metaphysicians of Tlön do not seek for the truth or even for verisimilitude, but rather for the astounding. They judge that metaphysics is a branch of fantastic literature. They know that a system is nothing more than the subordination of all aspects of the universe to any one such aspect. Even the phrase \"all aspects\" is rejectable, for it supposes the impossible addition of the present and of all past moments.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000081","text":"Nowadays, one of the churches of Tlön maintains platonically that such and such a pain, such and such a greenish-yellow colour, such and such a temperature, such and such a sound, etc., make up the only reality there is. All men, in the climactic instant of coitus, are the same man. All men who repeat one line of Shakespeare are William Shakespeare.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Tlön, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000082","text":"Writing long books is a laborious and impoverishing act of foolishness: expanding in five hundred pages an idea that could be perfectly explained in a few minutes. A better procedure is to pretend that those books already exist and to offer a summary, a commentary.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths (1942)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000083","text":"I have known that thing the Greeks knew not – uncertainty.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths (1942)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000084","text":"It seemed incredible to me that day without premonitions or symbols should be the one of my inexorable death.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000085","text":"I reflected that everything happens to a man precisely, precisely now. Centuries of centuries and only in the present do things happen; countless men in the air, on the face of the earth and the sea, and all that really is happening is happening to me . . .","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000086","text":"I foresee that man will resign himself each day to more atrocious undertakings; soon there will be no one but warriors and brigands; I give them this counsel: The author of an atrocious undertaking ought to imagine that he has already accomplished it, ought to impose upon himself a future as irrevocable as the past.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000087","text":"I thought of a labyrinth of labyrinths, of one sinuous spreading labyrinth that would encompass the past and the future and in some way involve the stars.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000088","text":"I thought that a man can be an enemy of other men, of the moments of other men, but not of a country: not of fireflies, words, gardens, streams of water, sunsets.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000089","text":"A labyrinth of symbols... An invisible labyrinth of time.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000090","text":"Ts'ui Pe must have said once: I am withdrawing to write a book. And another time: I am withdrawing to construct a labyrinth. Every one imagined two works; to no one did it occur that the book and the maze were one and the same thing.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000091","text":"I leave to the various futures (not to all) my garden of forking paths.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000092","text":"In the work of Ts'ui Pên, all possible outcomes occur; each one is the point of departure for other forkings. Sometimes, the paths of this labyrinth converge: for example, you arrive at this house, but in one of the possible pasts you are my enemy, in another, my friend.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000093","text":"Thus fought the heroes, tranquil their admirable hearts, violent their swords, resigned to kill and to die.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000094","text":"In a riddle whose answer is chess, what is the only prohibited word?","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000095","text":"Time forks perpetually toward innumerable futures. In one of them I am your enemy.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Garden of Forking Paths","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000096","text":"My undertaking is not difficult, essentially... I should only have to be immortal to carry it out.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"\"Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote\"","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000097","text":"There is no exercise of the intellect which is not, in the final analysis, useless. A philosophical doctrine begins as a plausible description of the universe; with the passage of the years it becomes a mere chapter — if not a paragraph or a name — in the history of philosophy.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"\"Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote\"","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000098","text":"Fame is a form—perhaps the worst form—of incomprehension.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"\"Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote\"","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000099","text":"Thinking, meditating, imagining are not anomalous acts – they are the normal respiration of the intelligence. To glorify the occasional exercise of that function, to treasure beyond price ancient and foreign thoughts, to recall with incredulous awe what some doctor universalis thought, is to confess our own languor, or our own barbarie. Every man should be capable of all ideas, and I believe that in the future he shall be.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"\"Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote\"","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000100","text":"The truth is that we live out our lives putting off all that can be put off; perhaps we all know deep down that we are immortal and that, sooner or later, all men will do and know all things.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000101","text":"That history should have imitated history was already sufficiently marvellous; that history should imitate literature is inconceivable....","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000102","text":"What one man does is something done, in some measure, by all men. For that reason a disobedience committed in a garden contaminates the human race; for that reason it is not unjust that the crucifixion of a single Jew suffices to save it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000103","text":"It's possible, but not interesting,\" Lonnrot answered. \"You will reply that reality hasn't the slightest need to be of interest. And I'll answer you that reality may avoid the obligation to be interesting, but that hypotheses may not. In the hypothesis you have postulated, chance intervenes largely. Here lies a dead rabbi; I should prefer a purely rabbinical explanation; not the imaginary mischances of an imaginary robber.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000104","text":"Maybe this crime belongs to the history of Jewish superstitions,\" murmmured Lönnrot. \"Like Christianity,\" the editor put in.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000105","text":"The execution was set for the 29th of March, at nine in the morning. This delay was due to a desire on the part of the authorities to act slowly and impersonally, in the manner of planets or vegetables.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000106","text":"Like every writer, he measured the virtues of other writers by their performance, and asked that they measure him by what he conjectured or planned.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000107","text":"The time for your labor has been granted.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000108","text":"Toward dawn, he dreamed that he was in hiding, in one of the naves of the Clementine Library. What are you looking for? a librarian wearing dark glasses asked him. I'm looking for God, Hladik replied. God, the librarian said, is in one of the letters on one of the pages of one of the four hundred thousand volumes in the Clementine. My parents and my parents' parents searched for that letter; I myself have gone blind searching for it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000109","text":"In adultery, there is usually tenderness and self-sacrifice; in murder, courage; in profanation and blasphemy, a certain satanic splendour. Judas elected those offences unvisited by any virtues: abuse of confidence and informing.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000110","text":"On the floor, and hanging on to the bar, squatted an old man, immobile as an object. His years had reduced and polished him as water does a stone or the generations of men do a sentence. He was dark, dried up, diminutive, and seemed outside time, situated in eternity.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Ficciones (1944)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000111","text":"I cannot walk through the suburbs in the solitude of the night without thinking that the night pleases us because it suppresses idle details, just as our memory does.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000112","text":"Music, states of happiness, mythology, faces belabored by time, certain twilights and certain places try to tell us something, or have said something we should not have missed, or are about to say something; this imminence of a revelation which does not occur is, perhaps, the aesthetic phenomenon.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000113","text":"Universal history is the history of a few metaphors.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000114","text":"In the course of a life devoted less to living than to reading, I have verified many times that literary intentions and theories are nothing more than stimuli and that the final work usually ignores or even contradicts them.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000115","text":"Wakefield\" prefigures Franz Kafka, but the latter modifies, and sharpens, the reading of \"Wakefield.\" The debt is mutual; a great writer creates his or her precursors. He or she creates them and in some fashion justifies them.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000116","text":"In the critic's vocabulary, the word \"precursor\" is indispensable, but it should be cleansed of all connotations of polemic or rivalry. The fact is that every writer creates his own precursors. His work modifies our conception of the past, as it will modify the future.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000117","text":"A book is more than a verbal structure or series of verbal structures; it is the dialogue it establishes with its reader and the intonation it imposes upon his voice and the changing and durable images it leaves in his memory. A book is not an isolated being: it is a relationship, an axis of innumerable relationships.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000118","text":"Literature is not exhaustible, for the sufficient and simple reason that a single book is not. A book is not an isolated entity: it is a narration, an axis of innumerable narrations. One literature differs from another, either before or after it, not so much because of the text as for the manner in which it is read.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000119","text":"The future is inevitable and precise, but it may not occur. God lurks in the gaps.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000120","text":"To fall in love is to create a religion that has a fallible god.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000121","text":"In the order of literature, as in others, there is no act that is not the coronation of an infinite series of causes and the source of an infinite series of effects.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Other Inquisitions (1952)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000122","text":"It is clear that there is no classification of the Universe that is not arbitrary and full of conjectures. The reason for this is very simple: we do not know what kind of thing the universe is.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Analytical Language of John Wilkins","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000123","text":"Cabe ir más lejos; cabe sospechar que no hay universo en el sentido orgánico, unificador, que tiene esa ambiciosa palabra. Si lo hay, falta conjeturar su propósito; falta conjeturar las palabras, las definiciones, las etimologías, las sinonimias, del secreto diccionario de Dios.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Analytical Language of John Wilkins","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000124","text":"The impossibility of penetrating the divine pattern of the universe cannot stop us from planning human patterns, even though we are conscious they are not definitive. The analytic language of Wilkins is not the least admirable of such patterns.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Analytical Language of John Wilkins","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000125","text":"I have suspected that history, real history, is more modest and that its essential dates may be, for a long time, secret. A Chinese prose writer has observed that the unicorn, because of its own anomaly, will pass unnoticed. Our eyes see what they are accustomed to seeing. Tacitus did not perceive the Crucifixion, although his book recorded it.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Modesty of History","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000126","text":"There is a flavor that our time (perhaps surfeited by the clumsy imitations of professional patriots) does not usually perceive without some suspicion: the fundamental flavor of the heroic.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"The Modesty of History","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000127","text":"Myth is at the beginning of literature, and also at its end.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Dreamtigers (1960)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000128","text":"Yo, que me figuraba el Paraíso / Bajo la especie de una biblioteca. I have always imagined Paradise as a kind of library.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Dreamtigers (1960)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000129","text":"The flattery of posterity is not worth much more than contemporary flattery, which is worth nothing.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Dreamtigers (1960)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000130","text":"Un hombre se propone la tarea de dibujar el mundo. A lo largo de los años puebla un espacio con imágenes de provincias, de reinos, de montañas, de bahías, de naves, de islas, de peces, de habitaciones, de instrumentos, de astros, de caballos y de personas. Poco antes de morir, descubre que ese paciente laberinto de líneas traza la imagen de su cara.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Dreamtigers (1960)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000131","text":"Well, [Lorca had] a gift for gab. For example, he makes striking metaphors, but I think he makes striking metaphors for him, because I think that his world was mostly verbal. I think that he was fond of playing words against each other, the contrast of words, but I wonder if he knew what he was doing.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Conversations with Jorge Luis Borges (1968)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000132","text":"This was the first time Remington rifles were used in the Argentine, and it tickles my fancy to think that the firm that shaves me every morning bears the same name as the one that killed my grandfather.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Autobiographical Notes (1970)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000133","text":"Of course, like all young men, I tried to be as unhappy as I could — a kind of Hamlet and Raskolnikov rolled into one.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Autobiographical Notes (1970)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000134","text":"I found America the friendliest, most forgiving, and most generous nation I had ever visited. We South Americans tend to think of things in terms of convenience, whereas people in the United States approach things ethically. This — amateur Protestant that I am — I admired above all. It even helped me overlook skyscrapers, paper bags, television, plastics, and the unholy jungle of gadgets.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Autobiographical Notes (1970)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000135","text":"Any time something is written against me, I not only share the sentiment but feel I could do the job far better myself. Perhaps I should advise would-be enemies to send me their grievances beforehand, with full assurance that they will receive my every aid and support. I have even secretly longed to write, under a pen name, a merciless tirade against myself.","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Autobiographical Notes (1970)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-borges-000136","text":"Jorge Luis Borges: a first introduction to the author's prose work","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-borges-000137","text":"The Jorge Luis Borges Center for Studies and Documentation","author":"Jorge Luis Borges","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:imagination","theme:philosophy","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000001","text":"When you find your path, you must not be afraid. You need to have sufficient courage to make mistakes. Disappointment, defeat, and despair are the tools God uses to show us the way.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000002","text":"The wise are wise only because they love.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000003","text":"When we least expect it, life sets us a challenge to test our courage and willingness to change; at such a moment, there is no point in pretending that nothing has happened or in saying that we are not ready. The challenge will not wait. Life does not look back. A week is more than enough time for us to decide whether or not to accept our destiny.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000004","text":"Terror, terror, terror. Life was a reign o terror in the shadow of the guillotine.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000005","text":"The two worst strategic mistakes to make are acting prematurely and letting an opportunity slip; to avoid this, the warrior treats each situation as if it were unique and never resorts to formulae, recipes or other people's opinions.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000006","text":"There is suffering in life, and there are defeats. No one can avoid them. But it's better to lose some of the battles in the struggles for your dreams than to be defeated without ever knowing what you're fighting for.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000007","text":"You drown not by falling into a river, but by staying submerged in it.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000008","text":"A disciple asked Hejasi: - I want to know what is the most funny thing about human beings. Hejasi said: - That they always think crooked: they’re in a hurry to grow, then lament their lost childhood, and soon lose the money they need to keep their health. \"They are so anxious about the future, that they neglect the present, and thus live in neither the present nor the future.\" \"They live as if they were never going to die, and die as if they had never lived.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000009","text":"Brazil is my way to see the world. Being born in that country means: \"you don't have a wall separating the physical reality from the magical reality.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000010","text":"As an author, I should be defending ‘intellectual property’, but I’m not. Pirates of the world, unite and pirate everything I’ve ever written!","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-coelho-000011","text":"We warriors of light must be prepared to have patience in difficult times and to know the Universe is conspiring in our favor, even though we may not understand how.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000012","text":"I ask myself: are defeats necessary? Well, necessary or not, they happen. When we first begin fighting for a dream, we have no experience and make mistakes. The secret of life, though, is to fall seven times and to get up eight times.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000013","text":"If you come here, you will find a hidden treasure.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000014","text":"I told you that your dream was a difficult one. It's the simple things in life that are the most extraordinary; only wise men are able to understand them.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000015","text":"At a certain point in our lives, we lose control of what's happening to us, and our lives become controlled by fate. That's the world's greatest lie.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000016","text":"There is one great truth on this planet: whoever you are, or whatever it is that you do, when you really want something, it's because that desire originated in the soul of the universe.... The soul of the world is nourished by people's happiness.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000017","text":"E quando você quer alguma coisa, todo o Universo conspira para que você realize seu desejo.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000018","text":"At that point in their lives, everything is clear and everything is possible. They are not afraid to dream, and to yearn for everything they would like to see happen to them in their lives. But, as time passes a mysterious force begins to convince them that it will be impossible for them to realize their destiny.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000019","text":"As he mused about these things, he realised that he had to choose between thinking of himself as the poor victim of a thief and as an adventurer in quest of his treasure.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000020","text":"He had worked for an entire year to make a dream come true, and that dream, minute by minute, was becoming less important. Maybe cause that wasn't really his dream.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000021","text":"We are afraid of losing what we have, whether it's our life or our possessions and property. But this fear evaporates when we understand that our life stories and the history of the world were written by the same hand.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000022","text":"If I am really a part of your dream, you'll come back one day.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000023","text":"If good things are coming, they will be a pleasant surprise,\" said the seer. \"If bad things are, and you know in advance, you will suffer greatly before they even occur.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000024","text":"The desert takes our dreams away from us, and they don't always return. We know that, and we are used to it. Those who don't return become a part of the clouds, a part of the animals that hide in the ravines and of the water that comes from the earth. They become part of everything... They become the Soul of the World.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000025","text":"One is loved because one is loved. No reason is needed for loving.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000026","text":"Tell your heart that the fear of suffering is worse than the suffering itself. And that no heart has ever suffered when it goes in search of its dreams, because every second of the search is a second's encounter with God and with eternity.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000027","text":"Don't think about what you've left behind, the alchemist said to the boy as they began to ride across the sands of the desert. \"Everything is written in the Soul of the World, and there it will stay forever.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000028","text":"If what one finds is made of pure matter, it will never spoil. If what you had found was only a moment of light, like the explosion of a star, you would find nothing on your return.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000029","text":"There is only one way to learn … It's through action.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000030","text":"A grain of sand is a moment of creation, and the universe has taken millions of years to create it.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000031","text":"It is said that the darkest hour of the night comes just before the dawn.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000032","text":"There is only one thing that makes a dream impossible to achieve: the fear of failure.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000033","text":"The wise men understood that this natural world is simply a guarantee that there exists a world that is perfect. God created the world so that, through its visible objects, men could understand his spiritual teachings and the marvels of his wisdom. That's what I mean by action.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000034","text":"Wherever your heart is, that is where you'll find your treasure.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000035","text":"It's true that everything has its Personal Legend, but one day that Personal Legend will be realized. So each thing has to transform itself into something better, and to acquire a new Personal Legend, until, someday, the Soul of the World becomes one thing only.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000036","text":"Love is the force that transforms and improves the Soul of the World. … It is we who nourish the Soul of the World, and the world we live in will be either better or worse, depending on whether we become better or worse. And that's where the power of love comes in. Because when we love, we always strive to become better than we are.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000037","text":"No matter what he does, every person on earth plays a central role in the history of the world. And normally he doesn't know it.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000038","text":"Your money saved us for three days. It's not often that money saves a person's life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000039","text":"Everything that happens once can never happen again. But everything that happens twice will surely happen a third time.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Alchemist (1988)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000040","text":"The parents always insisted on telling their child that their secret friends didn't exist — perhaps because they had forgotten that they too had spoken to their angel at one time. Or, who knows, perhaps they thought they lived in a world where there was no longer any place for angels. Disenchanted, the angels had returned to God's side, knowing that they could no longer impose their presence.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Valkyries (1992)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000041","text":"Perhaps they needn't even believe — it was enough that they needed angels, and the angels would return gladly.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Valkyries (1992)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000042","text":"We must never forget that spiritual experience is above all a practical experience of love. And with love, there are no rules.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000043","text":"Seek to live. Remembrance is for the old.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000044","text":"Pitiful is the person who is afraid of taking risks.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000045","text":"Lovers need to know how to lose themselves and then how to find themselves again.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000046","text":"Love is much like a dam: if you allow a tiny crack to form through which only a trickle of water can pass, that trickle will quickly bring down the whole structure, and soon no one will be able to control the force of the current. For when those walls come down, then love takes over, and it no longer matters what is possible or impossible; it doesn't even matter whether we can keep the loved one at our side. To love is to lose control.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000047","text":"There's nothing deeper than love. In fairy tales, the princesses kiss the frogs, and the frogs become princes. In real life, the princesses kiss princes, and the princes turn into frogs.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000048","text":"Life takes us by surprise and orders us to move toward the unknown — even when we don't want to and when we think we don't need to.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000049","text":"If pain must come, may it come quickly. Because I have a life to live, and I need to live it in the best way possible. If he has to make a choice, may he make it now. Then I will either wait for him or forget him.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000050","text":"Waiting is painful. Forgetting is painful. But not knowing which to do is the worst kind of suffering.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000051","text":"Even if loving meant leaving, or solitude, or sorrow, love was worth every penny of its price.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000052","text":"I am going to sit here with you by the river. If you go home to sleep, I will sleep in front of your house. And if you go away, I will follow you — until you tell me to go away. Then I'll leave. But I have to love you for the rest of my life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"By The River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept (1994)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000053","text":"Warriors of the light are not perfect. Their beauty lies in accepting this fact and still desiring to grow and to learn.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"' (1997)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000054","text":"A warrior of the light never confuses tension with anxiety.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"' (1997)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000055","text":"On 11 November 1997, Veronika decided that the moment to kill herself had — at last! — arrived.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000056","text":"When she opened her eyes, Veronika did not think \"this must be heaven\". Heaven would never use a fluorescent tube to light a room, and the pain — which started a fraction of a second later — was typical of the Earth. Ah, that Earth pain — unique, unmistakable.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000057","text":"I'll tell everyone that the children are my reason for living, when in reality my life is their reason for living.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000058","text":"Veronika brought her interior monologue to a close and made a promise to herself: she would not leave Villete alive. It was best to put an end to everything now, while she was still brave and healthy enough to die.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000059","text":"Look me in the eye and never forget what I'm about to tell you. There are only two prohibitions, one according to man's law, the other according to God's. Never force a sexual relationship on anyone, because that is considered to be rape. And never have sexual relations with children, because that is the worst of all sins. Apart from that, you're free. There's always someone who wants exactly what you want.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000060","text":"The great problem with poisoning by Bitterness was that the passions — hatred, love, despair, enthusiasm, curiosity — also ceased to manifest themselves. After a while, the embittered person felt no desire at all. They lacked the will either to live or to die, that was the problem.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000061","text":"You are someone who is different, but who wants to be the same as everyone else. And that in my view is a serious illness. God chose you to be different. Why are you disappointing God with this kind of attitude?","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000062","text":"You have two choices: to control your mind or to let your mind control you.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Veronika Decides to Die (1998)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000063","text":"When we meet someone and fall in love, we have a sense that the whole universe is on our side. And yet if something goes wrong, there is nothing left! How is it possible for the beauty that was there only minutes before to vanish so quickly? Life moves very fast. It rushes from heaven to hell in a matter of seconds.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Eleven Minutes (2003)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000064","text":"I can choose either to be a victim of the world or an adventurer in search of treasure. It's all a question of how I view my life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Eleven Minutes (2003)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000065","text":"Life always waits for some crisis to occur before revealing itself at its most brilliant.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Eleven Minutes (2003)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000066","text":"In love, no one can harm anyone else; we are each of us responsible for our own feelings and cannot blame someone else for what we feel. It hurt when I lost each of the various men I fell in love with. Now, though, I am convinced that no one loses anyone, because no one owns anyone. That is the true experience of freedom: having the most important thing in the world without owning it.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Eleven Minutes (2003)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000067","text":"Anyone who is in love is making love the whole time, even when they're not. When two bodies meet, it is just the cup overflowing. They can stay together for hours, even days. They begin the dance one day and finish it the next, or — such is the pleasure they experience — they may never finish it. No eleven minutes for them.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Eleven Minutes (2003)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000068","text":"I learned something recently: our true friends are those who are with us when the good things happen. They cheer us on and are pleased by our triumphs. False friends only appear at difficult times, with their sad, supportive faces, when, in fact, our suffering is serving to console them for their miserable lives...","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000069","text":"You want to know if the heart of a man or a woman can contain enough love for more than one person? … I think it's perfectly possible as long as one of those people doesn’t turn into … a Zahir.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000070","text":"In my world, everything is possible and everything is relative.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000071","text":"Everyone believes that the main aim in life is to follow a plan. They never ask if that plan is theirs or if it was created by another person. They accumulate experiences, memories, things, other people's ideas, and it is more than they can possibly cope with. And that is why they forget their dreams.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000072","text":"Stop being who you were and become who you are.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000073","text":"A brush with death always helps us to live our lives better.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000074","text":"That’s the problem, we do get used to things.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000075","text":"That is how I would have acted before my accident, but now my personal history had become unimportant. It had stopped being history and was once more becoming a legend, a search, an adventure, a journey into and away from myself. I was once more in a time which the things around me were changing and that is how I wanted it to be for the rest of my days.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Zahir (2005)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000076","text":"All my life I've learned to suffer in silence.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Witch of Portobello (2007)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000077","text":"What is a teacher? I'll tell you: it isn't someone who teaches something, but someone who inspires the student to give of her best in order to discover what she already knows.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Witch of Portobello (2007)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000078","text":"Love simply is. That is the testament of Athena or Sherine or Hagia Sofia — love is. No definitions. Love and don't ask too many questions. Just love.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"The Witch of Portobello (2007)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000079","text":"You feel that nothing you have learned has put down roots, that while you’re capable of entering the magical universe, you cannot remain submerged in it. You feel that all of this may be nothing but a fantasy dreamed up by people to fend off their fear of death.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000080","text":"I have only one certainty: there exists a parallel spiritual universe that impinges on the world in which we live. Apart from that, everything else seems absurd to me—sacred books, revelations, guides, manuals, ceremonies … and, what is worse, they appear to have no lasting effects.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000081","text":"That’s because, like everyone else on the planet, you believed that time would teach you to grow closer to God. But time doesn’t teach; it merely brings us a sense of weariness and of growing older.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000082","text":"Past and future exist only in our memory. The present moment, though, is outside of time, it’s Eternity. In India, they use the word ‘karma,’ for lack of any better term. It isn’t what you did in the past that will affect the present. It’s what you do in the present that will redeem the past and thereby change the future.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000083","text":"You think that you exist because you’re unhappy. Other people exist merely as a function of their problems and spend all their time talking compulsively about their children, their wives and husbands, school, work, friends. They never stop to think: I’m here. I am the result of everything that happened and will happen, but I’m here. If I did something wrong, I can put it right or at least ask forgiveness. If I did something right, that leaves me happier and more connected with the now”.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000084","text":"you discover that your old “I,” along with everything you ever learned, is absolutely no use at all in the face of those new challenges, and you begin to realize that buried deep in your unconscious mind there is someone much more interesting and adventurous and more open to the world and to new experiences.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000085","text":"Our life is a constant journey, from birth to death. The landscape changes, the people change, our needs change, but the train keeps moving. Life is the train, not the station. And what you’re doing now isn’t traveling, it’s just changing countries, which is completely different Understand what is going on inside you and you will understand what is going on inside everyone else.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000086","text":"Whenever I refused to follow my fate, something very hard to bear would happen in my life. Tragedy always brings about radical change in our lives, a change that is associated with the same principle: loss. When faced by any loss, there’s no point in trying to recover what has been; it’s best to take advantage of the large space that opens up before us and fill it with something new.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000087","text":"What did I do to deserve this?","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000088","text":"Lord, preserve me from tragedy and I will follow your desires.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000089","text":"Here I am, trying to persuade myself that I always give the best of myself, and nature is telling me exactly the opposite: anyone truly committed to life never stops walking.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000090","text":"Routine has nothing to do with repetition. To become really good at anything, you have to practice and repeat, practice and repeat, until the technique becomes intuitive.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000091","text":"What can’t be cured must be endured.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000092","text":"Every note leaves in each of us a memory, but it is the melody as a whole that tells a story, the story of someone wanting to get closer to another person and who keeps on trying, despite repeated rejections.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000093","text":"I can’t tell someone that their dreams are impossible.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000094","text":"If I were to persuade just one person to stop fighting for something they were convinced was worthwhile, I would end up persuading myself, and my whole life would be diminished.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000095","text":"So, in my relationships with men, I’ve always sought suffering, conflict, and despair.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000096","text":"Don’t let yourself be destroyed by a force that was placed in our hearts in order to make everything better.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000097","text":"The light of love flows out of my soul, but it can go nowhere because it’s blocked by pain. I could inhale and exhale every morning for the rest of my life, but that wouldn’t solve anything.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000098","text":"What hurts us is what heals us.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000099","text":"Life has been very hard on me, but, at the same time, it has taught me a great deal.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000100","text":"To live is to experience things, not sit around pondering the meaning of life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000101","text":"What we aim to do is calm the spirit and get in touch with the source from which everything comes, removing any trace of malice or egotism. If you spend too much time trying to find out what is good or bad about someone else, you’ll forget your own soul and end up exhausted and defeated by the energy you have wasted in judging others.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000102","text":"Lao-tzu’s words, was: place all your feelings outside of yourself and you will be renewed.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000103","text":"I don’t believe in God as you imagine Him to be, but I believe in many things that you could never even dream of.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000104","text":"I think to myself that this really isn’t something I should concern myself with.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000105","text":"“No one can learn to love by following a manual, and no one can learn to write by following a course. I’m not telling you to seek out other writers but to find people with different skills from yourself, because writing is no different from any other activity done with joy and enthusiasm”.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000106","text":"If I had to give you one piece of advice, it would be this: don’t be intimidated by other people’s opinions.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000107","text":"Only mediocrity is sure of itself, so take risks, and do what you really want to do.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000108","text":"Seek out people who aren’t afraid of making mistakes and who, therefore, do make mistakes. Because of that, their work often isn’t recognized, but they are precisely the kind of people who change the world and, after many mistakes, do something that will transform their own community completely”.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000109","text":"If someone is giving us something, that’s because we’re incapable of getting it for ourselves.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000110","text":"Love is the only thing that will save us, independent of any mistakes we may make. Love is always stronger.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000111","text":"Time neither moves nor is stationary. Time changes.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000112","text":"We learn in the past, but we are not the result of that. We suffered in the past, loved in the past, cried and laughed in the past, but that’s of no use to the present. The present has its challenges, its good and bad side. We can neither blame nor be grateful to the past for what is happening now. Each new experience of love has nothing whatsoever to do with past experiences. It’s always new.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000113","text":"People aren’t used to that way of thinking. They want everything to stay the same—and the consequence of that is pain,”.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000114","text":"We are not the person other people wish we were. We are who we decide to be.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000115","text":"It’s always easy to blame others. You can spend your entire life blaming the world, but your successes or failures are entirely your own responsibility. You can try to stop time, but it’s a complete waste of energy.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000116","text":"If you rely only on experience, you’ll simply keep applying old solutions to new problems. I know a lot of people who feel they have an identity only when they’re talking about their problems. That way, they exist, because their problems are linked to what they judge to be their history.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000117","text":"Love always triumphs over what we call death. That’s why there’s no need to grieve for our loved ones, because they continue to be loved and remain by our side.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000118","text":"Life is one long training session in preparation for what will come. Life and death lose their meaning; there are only challenges to be met with joy and overcome with tranquility.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000119","text":"First develop a strategy that utilizes everything around you. The best way to prepare for a challenge is to cultivate the ability to call on an infinite variety of responses.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000120","text":"I forgive the tears I was made to shed,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000121","text":"I forgive the pain and the disappointments,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000122","text":"I forgive the betrayals and the lies,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000123","text":"I forgive the slanders and intrigues,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000124","text":"I forgive the hatred and the persecution,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000125","text":"I forgive the blows that hurt me,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000126","text":"I forgive the stillborn hopes,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000127","text":"I forgive the hostility and jealousy,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000128","text":"I forgive the indifference and ill will,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000129","text":"I forgive the injustice carried out in the name of justice,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000130","text":"I forgive the anger and the cruelty,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000131","text":"I forgive the neglect and the contempt,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000132","text":"I forgive the world and all its evils.”","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000133","text":"I will be capable of loving, regardless of whether I am loved in return,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000134","text":"*Of giving, even when I have nothing,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000135","text":"Of working happily, even in the midst of difficulties,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000136","text":"Of holding out my hand, even when utterly alone and abandoned,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000137","text":"Of drying my tears, even while I weep,","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000138","text":"Of believing, even when no one believes in me.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000139","text":"The world is divided into those who understand me and those who don’t. In the case of the latter, I simply leave them to torment themselves trying to gain my sympathy.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000140","text":"I love you like a river that creates the right conditions for trees and bushes and flowers to flourish along its banks. I love you like a river that gives water to the thirsty and takes people where they want to go.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000141","text":"I love you like a river that understands that it must learn to flow differently over waterfalls and to rest in the shallows. I love you because we are all born in the same place, at the same source, which keeps us provided with a constant supply of water. And so, when we feel weak, all we have to do is wait a little. The spring returns, and the winter snows melt and fill us with new energy.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000142","text":"I love you like a river that begins as a solitary trickle in the mountains and gradually grows and joins other rivers until, after a certain point, it can flow around any obstacle in order to get where it wants.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000143","text":"I receive your love, and I give you mine. Not the love of a man for a woman, not the love of a father for a child, not the love of God for his creatures, but a love with no name and no explanation, like a river that cannot explain why it follows a particular course but simply flows onward. A love that asks for nothing and gives nothing in return; it is simply there. I will never be yours, and you will never be mine; nevertheless, I can honestly say: I love you, I love you, I love you.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000144","text":"I am not a foreigner, because I haven’t been praying to return safely home. I haven’t wasted my time imagining my house, my desk, my side of the bed. I am not a foreigner, because we are all traveling, we are all full of the same questions, the same tiredness, the same fears, the same selfishness, and the same generosity. I am not a foreigner, because, when I asked, I received.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000145","text":"When I knocked, the door opened. When I looked, I found.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000146","text":"Life is a dream from which we wake only when we meet death.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Aleph (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000147","text":"In 1974, the English archaeologist Sir Walter Wilkinson discovered another manuscript, this time written in three languages: Arabic, Hebrew, and Latin...On 30 November 2011, I received a copy of the text that he had mentioned at that first meeting. I transcribe it here.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000148","text":"Now that I am at the end of my life, I leave for those who come after me everything that I learned while I walked the face of this Earth. May they make good use of it.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000149","text":"This evening, in the same square where, a millennium ago, the Roman governor, Pontius Pilate, handed Jesus over to the mob to be crucified, a group of men and women of all ages went to see the Greek, whom we all know as the Copt... He did not seek to join any particular religion, and no one tried to persuade him otherwise. The Copt believes only in the present moment and what he calls Moira - the unknown god, the Divine Energy...","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000150","text":"It isn’t the absolute truth about life and death, but the thing that helps us to live and confront the challenges of day-to-day life. It isn’t what we learn from books, which serves only to fuel futile arguments about what happened or will happen; it is the knowledge that lives in the hearts of men and women of good will.... I am a learned man and yet...still don’t know quite what to say to you. But I will ask the Divine Energy to purify my heart.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000151","text":"You will ask me questions and I will answer them. That is what the teachers of Ancient Greece did; their disciples would ask them questions about problems they had not considered before and the teachers would answer them... We will speak, therefore, about our daily lives, about the difficulties we have had to face. That is all the future will be interested in, because I do not believe very much will change in the next thousand years.’","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000152","text":"Does a man who spent years preparing to climb the highest mountain in the world feel defeated when, on reaching that mountain, he discovers that nature has cloaked the summit in storm clouds? The man says... \"...the weather will change and, one day, I will make it to the top. Meanwhile, you’ll still be here waiting for me.”","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000153","text":"Does a young man, rejected by his first love, declare that love does not exist? The young man says to himself: “I’ll find someone better able to understand what I feel. And then I will be happy for the rest of my days.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000154","text":"In the cycle of nature there is no such thing as victory or defeat; there is only movement. The winter struggles to reign supreme, but in the end is obliged to accept spring’s victory, which brings with it flowers and happiness.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000155","text":"If victory is not theirs this time, it will be the next time. And if not the next time, then the time after that... The important thing is to get back on your feet. Only he who gives up is defeated. Everyone else is victorious.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000156","text":"The defeated are those who never fail. Defeat means that we lose a particular battle or war. Failure does not allow us to go on fighting.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000157","text":"Defeat is for those who, despite their fears, live with enthusiasm and faith. Defeat is for the valiant. Only they will know the honour of losing and the joy of winning.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000158","text":"Those who were never defeated seem happy and superior, masters of a truth they never had to lift a finger to achieve. They are always on the side of the strong. They’re like hyenas, who only eat the leavings of lions.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000159","text":"Without solitude, Love will not stay long by your side... Without solitude, no plant or animal can survive, no soil can remain productive for any length of time, no child can learn about life, no artist can create, no work can grow and be transformed.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000160","text":"Solitude is not the absence of Love, but its complement...Solitude is not the absence of company, but the moment when our soul is free to speak to us and help us decide what to do with our life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000161","text":"Therefore, blessed are those who do not fear solitude, who are not afraid of their own company, who are not always desperately looking for something to do, something to amuse themselves with, something to judge... If you are never alone, you cannot know yourself... And if you do not know yourself, you will begin to fear the void.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000162","text":"That feeling of uselessness is no respecter of age and never asks permission, but corrodes people’s souls, repeating over and over: ‘No one is interested in you, you’re nothing, the world doesn’t need your presence.’","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000163","text":"In a desperate attempt to give meaning to life, many turn to religion, because a struggle in the name of a faith is always a justification for some grand action, which could transform the world. ‘We are doing God’s work,’ they tell themselves. And they become devout followers, then evangelists, and finally, fanatics. They don’t understand that religion was created in order to share the mystery and to worship, not to oppress or convert others.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000164","text":"Nothing in this world is useless in the eyes of God. Not a leaf from a tree falls, not a hair from your head, not even an insect dies because it was of no use. Everything has a reason to exist... Don’t try to be useful. Try to be yourself: that is enough, and that makes all the difference. A life is never useless. Each soul that came down to Earth is here for a reason.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000165","text":"We are afraid to change because we think that, after much effort and sacrifice, we know our present world. And even though that world might not be the best of all worlds and even though we may not be entirely satisfied with it, at least it won’t give us any nasty surprises. We won’t go wrong. When necessary, we will make a few minor adjustments so that everything continues the same.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000166","text":"It’s nice to dream that we will have plenty of time in the future to do our travelling and that, one day, we will. It cheers us up because we know that we are capable of doing more than we do. Dreaming carries no risks. The dangerous thing is trying to transform your dreams into reality.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000167","text":"Joy. That is one of the main blessings of the All-Powerful. If we are happy, we are on the right road.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000168","text":"When they are lying in their tents, unable to sleep and overwhelmed by sadness and regret, they say to themselves: Tomorrow, and only tomorrow, will I take another step. Besides, I can always turn back, because I know the road, but one more step won’t make much difference.’ Until one day, without warning, the road stops testing the traveller and begins to treat him generously. The traveller’s troubled spirit takes pleasure in the beauties and the challenges of the new landscape.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000169","text":"What continues to trouble him is not what happens, but a fear that he won’t know how to deal with it. Once he has decided to follow his path and has no alternative, he discovers that he has great will power and that events bend to his decisions.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000170","text":"People always say: ‘It’s inner beauty that matters, not outer beauty.’ Well, that’s not true. If it were, why would flowers put so much energy into attracting bees? And why would raindrops transform themselves into a rainbow when they encounter the sun? Because nature longs for beauty, and is only satisfied when beauty can be exalted.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000171","text":"Outer beauty is inner beauty made visible, and it manifests itself in the light that flows from our eyes. It doesn’t matter if a person is badly dressed or doesn’t conform to our idea of elegance, or isn’t even concerned about impressing other people. The eyes are the mirror of the soul and reflect everything that seems to be hidden; and, like a mirror, they also reflect the person looking into them. So if the person looking into someone’s eyes has a dark soul, he will see only his own ugliness.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000172","text":"We are used to thinking that what we give is the same as what we receive, but people who love, expecting to be loved in return, are wasting their time. Love is an act of faith, not an exchange... Life is too short for us to keep important words, for example, ‘I love you’, locked in our hearts. But do not always expect to hear the same words back. We love because we need to love. Otherwise, love loses all meaning and the sun ceases to shine.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000173","text":"Sometimes, when loneliness seems about to crush everything, the only way to resist is to keep on loving.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000174","text":"Our great goal in life is to love. The rest is silence.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000175","text":"We need to love. Even when it leads us to the land where the lakes are made of tears, to that secret, mysterious place, the land of tears!","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000176","text":"It is better to have loved and lost than never to have loved at all.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000177","text":"We love because Love sets us free, and we say things that we once never even had the courage to whisper to ourselves.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000178","text":"No one can go back, but everyone can go forward. And tomorrow, when the sun rises, all you have to say to yourselves is: I am going to think of this day as the first day of my life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000179","text":"My smile is my way of saying: ‘You can destroy my body, but not my soul.’","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000180","text":"For the first time, I will smile without feeling guilty, because joy is not a sin... For the first time, I will avoid anything that makes me suffer, because suffering is not a virtue.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000181","text":"Love rules, but no one knows where it has its throne; in order to know that secret place, you must first submit to Love.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000182","text":"And if I’m alone in bed, I will go over to window, look up at the sky and feel certain that loneliness is a lie, because the Universe is there to keep me company.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000183","text":"Men and women whisper to each other because they have turned a sacred gesture into a sinful act. If two bodies merely join together, that is not sex, it is merely pleasure. Sex goes far beyond pleasure. In sex, relaxation and tension go hand in hand, as do pain and pleasure, shyness and the courage to go beyond one’s limits... It isn’t enough to imagine everything that might happen if we allowed ourselves to join not just our bodies, but our souls as well.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000184","text":"Let us plunge together, then, down the dangerous path of surrender. It may be dangerous, but it is the only path worth following.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000185","text":"Let us forget all that we are taught about how it is noble to give and humiliating to receive. Because for most people, generosity consists only in giving, but receiving is also an act of love. Allowing someone else to make us happy will make them happy too.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000186","text":"We were born alone and we will die alone. But, while we are on this planet, we must accept and glorify our act of faith through other people.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000187","text":"Arrogance attracts hatred and envy. Elegance arouses respect and Love. Arrogance causes us to humiliate our fellow man or woman. Elegance teaches us to walk in the light. Arrogance complicates words, because it believes that intelligence is only for the chosen few. Elegance transforms complex thoughts into something that everyone can understand.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000188","text":"When we are walking our chosen path, we walk elegantly, emanating light.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Manuscript Found in Accra (2012)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000189","text":"The weak are wicked. Goodness can only be expected from the strong.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Twitter","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-coelho-000190","text":"May love be your guide in every moment of your life.","author":"Paulo Coelho","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:destiny","theme:inspiration","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000001","text":"A little while ago, not much more than a few days ago, I was a child who went about in a world of colors, of hard and tangible forms. Everything was mysterious and something was hidden, guessing what it was was a game for me. If you knew how terrible it is to know suddenly, as if a bolt of lightning elucidated the earth. Now I live in a painful planet, transparent as ice; but it is as if I had learned everything at once in seconds.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1925 - 1945","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000002","text":"I’m more and more convinced it’s only through communism that we can become human.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1925 - 1945","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000003","text":"I drank because I wanted to drown my sorrows, but now the damned things have learned to swim.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1925 - 1945","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000004","text":"I paint self-portraits because I am so often alone, because I am the person I know best.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1925 - 1945","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000005","text":"I have suffered two grave accidents in my life, one in which a streetcar knocked me down... The other accident is Diego.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1946 - 1953","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000006","text":"Since Trotsky came to Mexico I have understood his error. I was never a Trotskyist.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1946 - 1953","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000007","text":"They thought I was a Surrealist, but I wasn't. I never painted dreams. I painted my own reality.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1946 - 1953","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000008","text":"I am not sick. I am broken. But I am happy to be alive as long as I can paint.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1946 - 1953","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000009","text":"Pies, para qué los quieroSi tengo alas para volar.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1946 - 1953","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000010","text":"I hope the exit is joyful and I hope never to return.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"1946 - 1953","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000011","text":"It's true I'm here, and I'm just as strange as you.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000012","text":"Frida Kahlo Bio, Photos, Paintings and Chronology","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000013","text":"Images of Frida Kahlo Paintings","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000014","text":"Frida Kahlo: Notas Sobre una Vida / Notes on a Life; photos of Frida in her daily life, and some of her written letters; Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000015","text":"[Illustration: Edgar Allan POE]","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000016","text":"I care not that my earthly lot)_ _The Conqueror Worm_ _Sonnet--To Zante_ _To M.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000017","text":"S.----_ _To the River----_ _A Dream_ _Al Aaraaf_ _To F----s S.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000018","text":"Maris Louise Shew)_ _Israfel_ _Fairy-land_ _Dreamland_ _Alone_ _Tamerlane_ _Tamerlane_","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000019","text":"Hear the sledges with the bells-- Silver bells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000020","text":"What a world of merriment their melody foretells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000021","text":"How they tinkle, tinkle, tinkle, In the icy air of night!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000022","text":"Hear the mellow wedding bells, Golden bells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000023","text":"What a world of happiness their harmony foretells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000024","text":"Through the balmy air of night How they ring out their delight!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000025","text":"From the molten golden-notes, And all in tune, What a liquid ditty floats To the turtle-dove that listens, while she gloats On the moon!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000026","text":"Oh, from out the sounding cells, What a gush of euphony voluminously wells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000027","text":"how it tells Of the rapture that impels To the swinging and the ringing Of the bells, bells, bells, Of the bells, bells, bells, bells, Bells, bells, bells-- To the rhyming and the chiming of the bells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000028","text":"Hear the loud alarum bells-- Brazen bells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000029","text":"What a tale of terror, now, their turbulency tells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000030","text":"In the startled ear of night How they scream out their affright!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000031","text":"Now--now to sit or never, By the side of the pale-faced moon.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000032","text":"What a tale their terror tells Of Despair!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000033","text":"How they clang, and clash, and roar!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000034","text":"What a horror they outpour On the bosom of the palpitating air!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000035","text":"Hear the tolling of the bells-- Iron bells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000036","text":"What a world of solemn thought their monody compels!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000037","text":"In the silence of the night, How we shiver with affright At the melancholy menace of their tone!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000038","text":"For every sound that floats From the rust within their throats Is a groan.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000039","text":"And his merry bosom swells With the paean of the bells!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000040","text":"I dwelt alone In a world of moan, And my soul was a stagnant tide, Till the fair and gentle Eulalie became my blushing bride-- Till the yellow-haired young Eulalie became my smiling bride.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000041","text":"Ah, less--less bright The stars of the night Than the eyes of the radiant girl!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000042","text":"And never a flake That the vapour can make With the moon-tints of purple and pearl, Can vie with the modest Eulalie's most unregarded curl-- Can compare with the bright-eyed Eulalie’s most humble and careless curl.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000043","text":"It was many and many a year ago, In a kingdom by the sea, That a maiden there lived whom you may know By the name of ANNABEL LEE; And this maiden she lived with no other thought Than to love and be loved by me.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000044","text":"I was a child and _she_ was a child, In this kingdom by the sea; But we loved with a love which was more than love-- I and my Annabel Lee; With a love that the wingèd seraphs of heaven Coveted her and me.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000045","text":"And this was the reason that, long ago, In this kingdom by the sea, A wind blew out of a cloud, chilling My beautiful Annabel Lee; So that her highborn kinsmen came And bore her away from me, To shut her up in a sepulchre In this kingdom by the sea.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000046","text":"The angels, not half so happy in heaven, Went envying her and me-- Yes!--that was the reason (as all men know, In this kingdom by the sea) That the wind came out of the cloud by night, Chilling and killing my Annabel Lee.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000047","text":"There are some qualities--some incorporate things, That have a double life, which thus is made A type of that twin entity which springs From matter and light, evinced in solid and shade.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000048","text":"There is a two-fold _Silence_--sea and shore-- Body and soul.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000049","text":"One dwells in lonely places, Newly with grass o'ergrown; some solemn graces, Some human memories and tearful lore, Render him terrorless: his name's \"No More.\" He is the corporate Silence: dread him not!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000050","text":"No power hath he of evil in himself; But should some urgent fate (untimely lot!) Bring thee to meet his shadow (nameless elf, That haunteth the lone regions where hath trod No foot of man), commend thyself to God!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000051","text":"Once upon a midnight dreary, while I pondered, weak and weary, Over many a quaint and curious volume of forgotten lore, While I nodded, nearly napping, suddenly there came a tapping, As of some one gently rapping, rapping at my chamber door.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000052","text":"Tis some visitor,\" I muttered, \"tapping at my chamber door-- Only this, and nothing more.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000053","text":"Ah, distinctly I remember it was in the bleak December, And each separate dying ember wrought its ghost upon the floor.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000054","text":"Eagerly I wished the morrow;--vainly I had sought to borrow From my books surcease of sorrow--sorrow for the lost Lenore-- For the rare and radiant maiden whom the angels name Lenore-- Nameless here for evermore.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000055","text":"Back into the chamber turning, all my soul within me burning, Soon again I heard a tapping somewhat louder than before.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000056","text":"Surely,\" said I, \"surely that is something at my window lattice: Let me see, then, what thereat is, and this mystery explore-- Let my heart be still a moment and this mystery explore;-- 'Tis the wind and nothing more.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000057","text":"But the raven, sitting lonely on the placid bust, spoke only That one word, as if his soul in that one word he did outpour.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000058","text":"Nothing further then he uttered--not a feather then he fluttered-- Till I scarcely more than muttered, \"other friends have flown before-- On the morrow _he_ will leave me, as my hopes have flown before.\" Then the bird said, \"Nevermore.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000059","text":"Then methought the air grew denser, perfumed from an unseen censer Swung by Seraphim whose footfalls tinkled on the tufted floor.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000060","text":"Wretch,\" I cried, \"thy God hath lent thee--by these angels he hath sent thee Respite--respite and nepenthe, from thy memories of Lenore!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000061","text":"Quaff, oh quaff this kind nepenthe and forget this lost Lenore!\" Quoth the Raven, \"Nevermore.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000062","text":"Prophet!\" said I, \"thing of evil--prophet still, if bird or devil!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000063","text":"Be that word our sign in parting, bird or fiend,\" I shrieked, upstarting-- \"Get thee back into the tempest and the Night's Plutonian shore!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000064","text":"Leave no black plume as a token of that lie thy soul hath spoken!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000065","text":"Leave my loneliness unbroken!--quit the bust above my door!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000066","text":"Take thy beak from out my heart, and take thy form from off my door!\" Quoth the Raven, \"Nevermore.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000067","text":"Thou wast all that to me, love, For which my soul did pine-- A green isle in the sea, love, A fountain and a shrine, All wreathed with fairy fruits and flowers, And all the flowers were mine.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000068","text":"Ah, dream to bright to last! Ah, starry Hope! that didst arise But to be overcast! A voice from out the Future cries, \"On! on!\"--but o'er the Past (Dim gulf!) my spirit hovering lies Mute, motionless, aghast!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000069","text":"For, alas! alas! with me The light of Life is o'er! \"No more--no more--no more--\" (Such language holds the solemn sea To the sands upon the shore) Shall bloom the thunder-blasted tree Or the stricken eagle soar!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000070","text":"And all my days are trances, And all my nightly dreams Are where thy grey eye glances, And where thy footstep gleams-- In what ethereal dances, By what eternal streams.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000071","text":"[Illustration: To One in Paradise]","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000072","text":"Ah, broken is the golden bowl!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000073","text":"Let the bell toll!--a saintly soul floats on the Stygian river; And, Guy de Vere, hast _thou_ no tear?--weep now or nevermore!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000074","text":"on yon drear and rigid bier low lies thy love, Lenore!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000075","text":"let the burial rite be read--the funeral song be sung!-- An anthem for the queenliest dead that ever died so young-- A dirge for her the doubly dead in that she died so young.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000076","text":"ye loved her for her wealth and hated her for her pride.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000077","text":"And when she fell in feeble health, ye blessed her--that she died!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000078","text":"How _shall_ the ritual, then, be read?--the requiem how be sung By you--by yours, the evil eye,--by yours, the slanderous tongue That did to death the innocence that died, and died so young?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000079","text":"_Peccavimus_; but rave not thus!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000080","text":"from fiends below, the indignant ghost is riven-- From Hell unto a high estate far up within the Heaven-- From grief and groan, to a golden throne, beside the King of Heaven!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000081","text":"Let no bell toll, then,--lest her soul, amid its hallowed mirth, Should catch the note as it doth float up from the damnèd Earth!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000082","text":"And I!--to-night my heart is light!--no dirge will I upraise, But waft the angel on her flight with a Paean of old days!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000083","text":"that my young life were a lasting dream!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000084","text":"My spirit not awakening, till the beam Of an Eternity should bring the morrow.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000085","text":"tho' that long dream were of hopeless sorrow, 'Twere better than the cold reality Of waking life, to him whose heart must be, And hath been still, upon the lovely earth, A chaos of deep passion, from his birth.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000086","text":"But should it be--that dream eternally Continuing--as dreams have been to me In my young boyhood--should it thus be given, 'Twere folly still to hope for higher Heaven.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000087","text":"I _have been_ happy, tho' in a dream.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000088","text":"I have been happy--and I love the theme: Dreams!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000089","text":"in their vivid colouring of life, As in that fleeting, shadowy, misty strife Of semblance with reality, which brings To the delirious eye, more lovely things Of Paradise and Love--and all our own!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000090","text":"Than young Hope in his sunniest hour hath known.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000091","text":"I saw thee once--once only--years ago: I must not say _how_ many--but _not_ many.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000092","text":"Clad all in white, upon a violet bank I saw thee half-reclining; while the moon Fell on the upturn'd faces of the roses, And on thine own, upturn'd--alas, in sorrow!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000093","text":"Was it not Fate, that, on this July midnight-- Was it not Fate, (whose name is also Sorrow,) That bade me pause before that garden-gate, To breathe the incense of those slumbering roses?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000094","text":"No footstep stirred: the hated world all slept, Save only thee and me.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000095","text":"(Oh, Heaven!--oh, God How my heart beats in coupling those two words!) Save only thee and me.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000096","text":"I paused--I looked-- And in an instant all things disappeared.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000097","text":"(Ah, bear in mind this garden was enchanted!)","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000098","text":"The pearly lustre of the moon went out: The mossy banks and the meandering paths, The happy flowers and the repining trees, Were seen no more: the very roses' odours Died in the arms of the adoring airs.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000099","text":"All--all expired save thee--save less than thou: Save only the divine light in thine eyes-- Save but the soul in thine uplifted eyes.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000100","text":"I saw but them--they were the world to me!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000101","text":"I saw but them--saw only them for hours, Saw only them until the moon went down.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000102","text":"What wild heart-histories seemed to lie enwritten Upon those crystalline, celestial spheres!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000103","text":"How dark a woe, yet how sublime a hope! How silently serene a sea of pride! How daring an ambition; yet how deep-- How fathomless a capacity for love!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000104","text":"But now, at length, dear Dian sank from sight, Into a western couch of thunder-cloud; And thou, a ghost, amid the entombing trees Didst glide away.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000105","text":"_Only thine eyes remained;_ They _would not_ go--they never yet have gone; Lighting my lonely pathway home that night, _They_ have not left me (as my hopes have) since; They follow me--they lead me through the years.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000106","text":"They are my ministers--yet I their slave.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000107","text":"Their office is to illumine and enkindle-- My duty, _to be saved_ by their bright light, And purified in their electric fire, And sanctified in their elysian fire.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000108","text":"In the greenest of our valleys By good angels tenanted, Once a fair and stately palace-- Radiant palace--reared its head. In the monarch Thought's dominion-- It stood there! Never seraph spread a pinion Over fabric half so fair!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000109","text":"Banners yellow, glorious, golden, On its roof did float and flow, (This--all this--was in the olden Time long ago,) And every gentle air that dallied, In that sweet day, Along the ramparts plumed and pallid, A wingèd odour went away.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000110","text":"Wanderers in that happy valley, Through two luminous windows, saw Spirits moving musically, To a lute's well-tuned law, Round about a throne where, sitting (Porphyrogene!) In state his glory well befitting, The ruler of the realm was seen.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000111","text":"And all with pearl and ruby glowing Was the fair palace door, Through which came flowing, flowing, flowing, And sparkling evermore, A troop of Echoes, whose sweet duty Was but to sing, In voices of surpassing beauty, The wit and wisdom of their king.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000112","text":"[Illustration: The Haunted Palace]","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000113","text":"But evil things, in robes of sorrow, Assailed the monarch's high estate.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000114","text":"(Ah, let us mourn!--for never morrow Shall dawn upon him desolate!) And round about his home the glory That blushed and bloomed, Is but a dim-remembered story Of the old time entombed.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000115","text":"I stand amid the roar Of a surf-tormented shore, And I hold within my hand Grains of the golden sand-- How few!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000116","text":"yet how they creep Through my fingers to the deep, While I weep--while I weep!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000117","text":"can I not grasp Them with a tighter clasp?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000118","text":"can I not save _One_ from the pitiless wave?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000119","text":"Is _all_ that we see or seem But a dream within a dream?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000120","text":"Death has reared himself a throne In a strange city lying alone Far down within the dim West, Where the good and the bad and the worst and the best Have gone to their eternal rest.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000121","text":"There shrines and palaces and towers (Time-eaten towers that tremble not!) Resemble nothing that is ours.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000122","text":"Around, by lifting winds forgot, Resignedly beneath the sky The melancholy waters lie.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000123","text":"Resignedly beneath the sky The melancholy waters lie.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000124","text":"So blend the turrets and shadows there That all seem pendulous in air, While from a proud tower in the town Death looks gigantically down.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000125","text":"[Illustration: The City in the Sea]","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000126","text":"There open fanes and gaping graves Yawn level with the luminous waves; But not the riches there that lie In each idol's diamond eye-- Not the gaily-jewelled dead Tempt the waters from their bed; For no ripples curl, alas!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000127","text":"Along that wilderness of glass-- No swellings tell that winds may be Upon some far-off happier sea-- No heavings hint that winds have been On seas less hideously serene.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000128","text":"The wave--there is a movement there!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000129","text":"As if the towers had thrust aside, In slightly sinking, the dull tide-- As if their tops had feebly given A void within the filmy Heaven.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000130","text":"The waves have now a redder glow-- The hours are breathing faint and low-- And when, amid no earthly moans, Down, down that town shall settle hence, Hell, rising from a thousand thrones, Shall do it reverence.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000131","text":"[F---- is, presumably, Mrs. Frances Sargent Osgood]","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000132","text":"Beloved! amid the earnest woes That crowd around my earthly path-- (Drear path, alas! where grows Not even one lonely rose)-- My soul at least a solace hath In dreams of thee, and therein knows An Eden of bland repose.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000133","text":"And thus thy memory is to me Like some enchanted far-off isle In some tumultuous sea-- Some ocean throbbing far and free With storms--but where meanwhile Serenest skies continually Just o'er that one bright island smile.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000134","text":"At midnight, in the month of June, I stand beneath the mystic moon.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000135","text":"An opiate vapour, dewy, dim, Exhales from out her golden rim, And, softly dripping, drop by drop, Upon the quiet mountain top, Steals drowsily and musically Into the universal valley.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000136","text":"The rosemary nods upon the grave; The lily lolls upon the wave; Wrapping the fog about its breast, The ruin moulders into rest; Looking like Lethe, see!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000137","text":"the lake A conscious slumber seems to take, And would not, for the world, awake.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000138","text":"where lies Irene, with her Destinies!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000139","text":"can it be right-- This window open to the night?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000140","text":"Oh, lady dear, hast thou no fear?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000141","text":"Why and what art thou dreaming here?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000142","text":"Sure thou art come o'er far-off seas, A wonder to these garden trees!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000143","text":"strange thy dress, Strange, above all, thy length of tress, And this all solemn silentness!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000144","text":"Oh, may her sleep, Which is enduring, so be deep!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000145","text":"Heaven have her in its sacred keep!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000146","text":"This chamber changed for one more holy, This bed for one more melancholy, I pray to God that she may lie For ever with unopened eye, While the pale sheeted ghosts go by!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000147","text":"Oh, may her sleep As it is lasting, so be deep!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000148","text":"Soft may the worms about her creep!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000149","text":"It was the dead who groaned within.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000150","text":"Here once, through an alley Titanic, Of cypress, I roamed with my Soul-- Of cypress, with Psyche, my Soul.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000151","text":"But Psyche, uplifting her finger, Said--\"Sadly this star I mistrust-- Her pallor I strangely mistrust:-- Oh, hasten!--oh, let us not linger!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000152","text":"Oh, fly!--let us fly!--for we must.\" In terror she spoke, letting sink her Wings until they trailed in the dust-- In agony sobbed, letting sink her Plumes till they trailed in the dust-- Till they sorrowfully trailed in the dust.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000153","text":"I replied--\"This is nothing but dreaming: Let us on by this tremulous light!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000154","text":"Let us bathe in this crystalline light!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000155","text":"Its Sybilic splendour is beaming With Hope and in Beauty to-night:-- See!--it flickers up the sky through the night!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000156","text":"Ah, we safely may trust to its gleaming, And be sure it will lead us aright-- We safely may trust to a gleaming That cannot but guide us aright, Since it flickers up to Heaven through the night.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000157","text":"Well I know, now, this dim lake of Auber-- This misty mid region of Weir-- Well I know, now, this dank tarn of Auber, This ghoul-haunted woodland of Weir.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000158","text":"Of late, eternal Condor years So shake the very Heaven on high With tumult as they thunder by, I have no time for idle cares Through gazing on the unquiet sky.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000159","text":"And when an hour with calmer wings Its down upon my spirit flings-- That little time with lyre and rhyme To while away--forbidden things!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000160","text":"My heart would feel to be a crime Unless it trembled with the strings.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000161","text":"true daughter of Old Time thou art!","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000162","text":"Who alterest all things with thy peering eyes.","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000163","text":"Why preyest thou thus upon the poet's heart, Vulture, whose wings are dull realities?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-kahlo-000164","text":"or how deem thee wise, Who wouldst not leave him in his wandering To seek for treasure in the jewelled skies, Albeit he soared with an undaunted wing?","author":"Frida Kahlo","source":"Frida Kahlo — Letters","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:identity","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from public-domain anthology; specific poem/letter not attributed"},{"id":"latin-paz-000001","text":"There can be no society without poetry, but society can never be realized as poetry, it is never poetic. Sometimes the two terms seek to break apart. They cannot.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-paz-000002","text":"To fight evil is to fight ourselves.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-paz-000003","text":"Between going and staying the day wavers,","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-paz-000004","text":"The Hindu genius is a love for abstraction and, at the same time, a passion for the concrete image. At times It is rich, at others prolix. It has created the most lucid and the most instinctive art. It is abstract and realistic, sexual and intellectual, pedantic and sublime. It lives between extremes, it embraces the extremes, rooted in the earth and drawn to an invisible beyond.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-paz-000005","text":"And to fill all these white pages that are left for me with the same monotonous question: at what hour do the hours end?","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Clerk's Vision (1949)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000006","text":"The first deaths will barely swell the daily count, and no one in the statistics bureau will notice that extra zero. But after a while everyone will begin to look at each other and ask: what's happening? Because for months doors and windows are going to rattle, furniture and trees will creak.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Clerk's Vision (1949)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000007","text":"Death is a mirror which reflects the vain gesticulations of the living. The whole motley confusion of acts, occasions, regrets and hopes which is the life of each one of us finds in death, not meaning or explanation, but an end.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Labyrinth of Solitude (1950)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000008","text":"The word \"death\" is not pronounced in New York, in Paris, in London, because it burns the lips. The Mexican, in contrast, is familiar with death, jokes about it, caresses it, sleeps with it, celebrates it; it is one of his favorite toys and his most steadfast love. True, there is perhaps as much fear in his attitude as in that of others, but at least death is not hidden away; he looks at it it face to face, with impatience, disdain or irony.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Labyrinth of Solitude (1950)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000009","text":"Modern man likes to pretend that his thinking is wide-awake. But this wide-awake thinking has led us into the mazes of a nightmare in which the torture chambers are endlessly repeated in the mirrors of reason.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Labyrinth of Solitude (1950)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000010","text":"willow of crystal, a poplar of water, a pillar of fountain by the wind drawn over, tree that is firmly rooted and that dances, turning course of a river that goes curving, advances and retreats, goes roundabout, arriving forever:","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Sun Stone (1957)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000011","text":"Man does not speak because he thinks; he thinks because he speaks. Or rather, speaking is no different than thinking: to speak is to think.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Alternating Current (1967)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000012","text":"If we are a metaphor of the universe, the human couple is the metaphor par excellence, the point of intersection of all forces and the seed of all forms. The couple is time recaptured, the return to the time before time.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Alternating Current (1967)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000013","text":"Art\" is an invention of aesthetics, which in turn is an invention of philosophers…what we call art is a game.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Alternating Current (1967)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000014","text":"To read a poem is to hear it with our eyes; to hear it is to see it with our ears.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Alternating Current (1967)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000015","text":"Images, memories, fragmentary shapes and forms — all those sensations, visions, half-thoughts that appear and disappear in the wink of an eye, as one sets forth to meet…. The path also disappears as I think of it, as I say it.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Monkey Grammarian (1974)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000016","text":"It is not proper to project our feelings onto things or to attribute our own sensations and passions to them. Can it also be improper to see in them a guide, a way of life? To learn the art of remaining motionless amid the agitation of the whirlwind, to learn to remain still and to be as transparent as this fixed light amid the frantic branches — this may be a program for life.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Monkey Grammarian (1974)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000017","text":"Ought I to say that the form of change is fixity, or more precisely, that change is an endless search for fixity? A nostalgia for inertia: indolence and its frozen paradises. Wisdom lies neither in fixity nor in change, but in the dialectic between the two. A constant coming and going: wisdom lies in the momentary. It is transition. But the moment I say transition, the spell is broken. Transition is not wisdom, but a simple going toward… Transition vanishes: only thus is it transition.","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"The Monkey Grammarian (1974)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-paz-000018","text":"Poetry selections, translations by Eliot Weinberger","author":"Octavio Paz","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:philosophy","theme:solitude","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican","tradition:poetry"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000001","text":"Fear is inevitable, I have to accept that, but I cannot allow it to paralyze me.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000002","text":"He realized...that the loudest are the least sincere, that arrogance is a quality of the ignorant, and that flatterers tend to be vicious.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000003","text":"Where does taste end and smell begin?","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000004","text":"Silence before being born, silence after death: life is nothing but noise between two unfathomable silences.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000005","text":"For women, the best aphrodisiacs are words. The G-spot is in the ears. He who looks for it below there is wasting his time.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000006","text":"Photographs deceive time, freezing it on a piece of cardboard where the soul is silent.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-allende-000007","text":"When Irina Bazili began working at Lark House in 2010, she was twenty-three years old but already had few illusions about life. (first line)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Japanese Lover (2015)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000008","text":"There are a lot of good people, Irina, but they keep quiet about it. It’s the bad ones who make a lot of noise, and that’s why they get noticed...\" (p103)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Japanese Lover (2015)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000009","text":"...you shouldn't stay trapped in the past or be frightened of the future. You only have one life, but if you live it well, that’s enough. The only reality is now, today. What are you waiting for to be happy? Every day counts, I can tell you!\" (p193)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Japanese Lover (2015)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000010","text":"...We are all born happy. Life gets us dirty along the way, but we can clean it up. Happiness is not exuberant or noisy, like pleasure or joy; it’s silent, tranquil, and gentle; it’s a feeling of satisfaction inside that begins with self-love...\" (p194)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Japanese Lover (2015)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000011","text":"Write what should not be forgotten.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Japanese Lover (2015)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000012","text":"our demons lose their power when we pull them out of the depths where they hide and look them in the face in broad daylight. (p249)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Maya's Notebook (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000013","text":"“It’s easy to judge others if you’ve never suffered an experience like that” (p250)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Maya's Notebook (2011)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000014","text":"I am Inés Suárez, a townswoman of the loyal city of Santiago de Nueva Extremadura in the kingdom of Chile, writing in the year of Our Lord 1580. (first line)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Inés of My Soul (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000015","text":"How accommodating love is; it forgives everything. (p10)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Inés of My Soul (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000016","text":"They relish seeing strong women like you and me humiliated. They cannot forgive us that we triumphed where so many others fail...Courage is a virtue appreciated in a male but considered a defect in our gender. Bold women are a threat to a world that is out of balance, in favor of men. That is why they work so hard to mistreat and destroy us.\" (p264)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Inés of My Soul (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000017","text":"Alexander Cold awakened at dawn, startled by a nightmare. (first line)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Inés of My Soul (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000018","text":"With age, you acquire a certain humility...The longer I live, the more uninformed I feel. Only the young have an explanation for everything. At your age, you can afford to commit the sin of arrogance, and it doesn't matter much if you look ridiculous\" (p50)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Inés of My Soul (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000019","text":"Jealousy. The person who hasn't felt it cannot know how much it hurts, or imagine the madness committed in its name. (p368)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Portrait in Sepia (2000)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000020","text":"love is a free contract that begins with a spark and can end the same way. A thousand dangers threaten love, but if the couple defends it, it can be saved; it can grow like a tree and give shade and fruit, but that happens only when both partners participate. (p369)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Portrait in Sepia (2000)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000021","text":"Memory is fiction. We select the brightest and the darkest, ignoring what we are ashamed of, and so embroider the broad tapestry of our lives. (p433)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Portrait in Sepia (2000)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000022","text":"Tell me a story,\" I say to you.\"What about?\"\"Tell me a story you have never told anyone before. Make it up for me.\" (last lines of Prologue)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Stories of Eva Luna (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000023","text":"She went by the name of Belisa Crepusculario, not because she had been baptized with that name or given it by her mother, but because she herself had searched until she found the poetry of \"beauty\" and \"twilight\" and cloaked herself in it. She made her living selling words. (first lines of \"Two Words\")","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The Stories of Eva Luna (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000024","text":"She sowed in my mind the idea that reality is not only what we see on the surface; it has a magical dimension as well and, if we so desire, it is legitimate to enhance it and color it to make our journey through life less trying. (p22)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Eva Luna (1987)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000025","text":"That was a good time in my life, in spite of having the sensation of floating on a cloud, surrounded by both lies and things left unspoken. Occasionally I thought I glimpsed the truth, but soon found myself once again lost in a forest of ambiguities. (p125)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Eva Luna (1987)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000026","text":"Barrabás came to us by sea, the child Clara wrote in her delicate calligraphy. She was already in the habit of writing down important matters, and afterward, when she was mute, she also recorded trivialities, never suspecting that fifty years later I would use her notebooks to reclaim the past and overcome terrors of my own. (first lines)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000027","text":"...Captain Longfellow—who, like most Englishmen, was kinder to animals than to people... (p31)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000028","text":"“This is to assuage our conscience, darling\" she would explain to Blanca. \"But it doesn't help the poor. They don't need charity; they need justice” (p162)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000029","text":"My son, the Holy Church is on the right, but Jesus Christ was always on the left.” (p182)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000030","text":"He felt that Christianity, like almost all forms of superstition, made men weaker and more resigned, and that the point was not to await some reward in the sky but to fight for one’s rights on earth. (p255)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000031","text":"Blanca argued that her reading should be monitored because there were certain things that were inappropriate for her age, but her Uncle Jaime felt that people never read what did not interest them and that if it interested them that meant they were sufficiently mature to read it. (p311)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000032","text":"The man and the little girl looked at each other, recognizing themselves in the other’s eyes. (p319)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000033","text":"Public opinion wouldn’t stand for it,” Gómez replied. “This is a democracy. It’s not a dictatorship and it never will be.” “We always think things like that only happen elsewhere,” said Miguel, “until they happen to us too.” (p367)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000034","text":"...and on the date stipulated by law the left calmly came to power. And on that date the right began to stockpile hatred. (p392)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000035","text":"She felt that everything was made of glass, as fragile as a sigh... (p430)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000036","text":"The coup gave them a chance to put into practice what they had learned in their barracks: blind obedience, the use of arms, and other skills that soldiers can master once they silence the scruples of their hearts. (p436)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000037","text":"The Poet’s funeral had turned into the symbolic burial of freedom. (p441)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000038","text":"I told her she had run an enormous risk rescuing me, and she smiled. It was then I understood that the days of Colonel Garcia and all those like him are numbered, because they have not been able to destroy the spirit of these women. (p487)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"The House of the Spirits (1982)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000039","text":"Because she lived under the big umbrella of my grandfather and she didn't have any education - she had three kids, had been abandoned by her husband, had no money - it was a horrible life. The only way she could get attention from her father or anybody else was by being sick. She didn't do it consciously. As a child I felt impotent and guilty because I felt that I couldn't help her in any way.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from Interviews","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000040","text":"Thank God – because what are you going to write about if you don’t struggle as a child? I don’t think that you become creative because you have struggled, no, but creative people are fuelled by anger and passion, and haunted by demons and memories.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from Interviews","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000041","text":"It would have been much better if I had started [writing novels] at 19. But I couldn't. I had to support a family, I wasn't ready. And I think I needed to lose my country to start writing, because The House of the Spirits is an attempt to recreate the country I had lost, the family I had lost.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from Interviews","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000042","text":"The theme of displacement is very natural for me. It always comes up in my books because I have been a foreigner all my life and I don’t feel I belong anywhere. I’m an immigrant.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from Interviews","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000043","text":"I imagined the structure of the novel like a braid. My job was to blend three strands evenly and neatly. Each piece of the braid represented one of the stories. The characters were very different but they had something in common: they were emotionally wounded by events of their past.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from Interviews","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000044","text":"I never try to give a message in my fiction. When I see that an author is trying to preach to me in a novel, I feel insulted. If I find a message, it should come between the lines; I will discover it if it resonates with me. The ideas, feelings and experiences of the author appear unavoidably in the writing.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from Interviews","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000045","text":"I can only write fiction in Spanish, because it is for me a very organic process that I can only do in my native language.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000046","text":"Everybody has a story and all stories are interesting if they are told in the right tone.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000047","text":"People are complex and complicated—they seldom show all the aspects of their personalities. Characters should be that way too.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000048","text":"To me a short story is like an arrow; it has to have the right direction from the beginning and you have to know exactly where you're aiming.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000049","text":"a novel is patient and daily work, like embroidering a tapestry of many colors. You go slowly, you have a pattern in mind. But all of a sudden you turn it and realize that it’s something else.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000050","text":"Happy endings usually don't work for me. I like open endings. I trust the reader’s imagination.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000051","text":"Pain is universal. We all experience pain, loss, and death the same way.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000052","text":"The death of a child is the oldest sorrow of women. Mothers have lost children for millennia. It is only a privileged few who can expect all of their children to live.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000053","text":"I work with emotions; language is the tool, the instrument.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000054","text":"It’s strange that my work has been classified as magic realism because I see my novels as just being realistic literature. They say that if Kafka had been born in Mexico he would have been a realistic writer. So much depends on where you were born.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000055","text":"the awareness of how powerful the written word can be: how you can tap into that world that we are talking about and discover things that would have been impossible to know if you didn't have that connection to a collective knowledge that comes through the writing.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000056","text":"Short stories come to you whole. A novel is work—work, work, work—and then one day it’s over; it’s finished. But a short story is something that happens to you—it’s like catching the flu.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000057","text":"Who wants to be in the mainstream?...Being marginal is like being a new immigrant. If you can transform marginality into something positive, instead of dwelling on it as something negative, it’s a wonderful source of strength.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000058","text":"there are more similarities than differences when it comes to gender. Essentially, human beings are very similar, but we are stuck in the differences instead of highlighting the similarities.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000059","text":"I have been a feminist all my life, fighting for feminist issues. When I was young, I fought aggressively. I was a warrior then. And now I am becoming more aware of those essential things we men and women have to explore and that could really bring us together. But don't get me wrong: I am a feminist and a very proud one!","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000060","text":"you will find elements of magic realism in literature from all over the world—not just in Latin America. You will find it in Scandinavian sagas, in African poetry, in Indian literature written in English, in American literature written by ethnic minorities. Writers like Salman Rushdie, Toni Morrison, Barbara Kingsolver, and Alice Hoffman all use this style.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000061","text":"For a while, in the U.S. and Europe, a logical and practical approach to literature prevailed, but it didn't last very long. That’s because life is full of mystery. And the goal of literature is to explore those mysteries. It actually enlarges your horizons. When you allow dreams, visions, and premonitions to enter into your everyday life and your work as a writer, reality seems to expand.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000062","text":"I do believe in destiny. I believe that we are dealt a hand of cards and we have to play the game of life as best we can. And often the cards are marked.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000063","text":"I try to write the first sentence in a state of trance, as if somebody else was writing it through me. That first sentence usually determines the whole book. It’s a door that opens to an unknown territory that I have to explore with my characters. And slowly, as I write, the story seems to unfold itself, in spite of me. It just happens.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000064","text":"Writing is like training to be an athlete. There is a lot of training and work that nobody sees in order to compete. The writer needs to write every day, just as the athlete needs to train. Much of the writing will never be used, but it is essential to do it. I always tell my young students to write at least one good page a day. At the end of the year they will have at least 360 good pages. That is a book.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"from interviews collected on author's website","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000065","text":"The role of the United States, not only in Latin America, but in many other places in the world, is unknown by many people in the United States. People here don’t know what the CIA and the American government has done abroad. And we know, because we are the ones who suffered it.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"with Democracy Now (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000066","text":"We see stuff on TV that doesn’t look real. It looks like a video game. We don’t see the collateral damage.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"with Democracy Now (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000067","text":"When I came to this country, I was willing to embrace everything that was good, fight against everything I thought was awful, and not lose what I brought with me, which is my language, my traditions, my way of living, hospitality, and many things that we Latins have.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"with Democracy Now (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000068","text":"What shocks me about the issue of immigration is that globally, capital has no borders. Money goes wherever money wants to go. There are no borders, no laws, nothing, for the capitalists. And yet, for labor, for the workers, there are fences, electrified fences and bullets.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"with Democracy Now (2006)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000069","text":"I think that the reason to live is to learn. We come here to experience through the body things that the spirit could not experience otherwise. So we need this body, and we have to transform this body into a temple of learning. (1997)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Conversations with Isabel Allende (1999)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000070","text":"I was influenced by all of them-by García Márquez, by Carlos Fuentes, Jorge Luis Borges, Julio Cortázar, José Donoso, so many of them-some of my own generation, like Eduardo Galeano. It's easy for me to write because I don't have to invent anything. They already found a voice, a way of telling us to ourselves, so it's easy. (1994)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Conversations with Isabel Allende (1999)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000071","text":"when you look for the motivations you always go to the basic instincts, to the basic emotions, the basic things that have moved humankind always. That's what all writers write about, ultimately. What did Shakespeare write about? Jealousy, love, sex, power, greed, the same stuff that soap operas and the Bible are made of. It's always the same. (1994)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Conversations with Isabel Allende (1999)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000072","text":"There is a wonderful sentence, a statement, by one of Bertolt Brecht's characters, he says: \"I am that man that goes around with a brick in his hand, to show the world how his house was.\" And that's the way I feel about my books in a way, that they are my bricks. I can show people what I believe my world was, so I've not lost it. (1990)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Conversations with Isabel Allende (1999)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000073","text":"The best literature in this country now is being written by minorities, black women first, Chinese Americans, Chicanos, Japanese-Americans. These people are writing wonderful literature that totally defies the standards of WASP literature that is always in the New York Times, and I love it. (1990)","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"Conversations with Isabel Allende (1999)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000074","text":"I acknowledge that One Hundred Years, like the works of Borges, Cortázar, Donoso, Neruda, Amado, among others, opened the road for me.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"In Interviews with Latin American Writers (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000075","text":"The written word is an act of human solidarity. I write so that people will love each other more.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"In Interviews with Latin American Writers (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000076","text":"The political future of Chile is a democracy, without a doubt.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"In Interviews with Latin American Writers (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000077","text":"I don't pretend to be anyone's voice. I have been very lucky to be published in Europe, and I say lucky because there are women who have been writing in Latin America since the seventeenth century, like Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz. The problem is that few people ever talk about them. Their work is rarely taught at the universities, there is no literary criticism on them, and they are not published, translated or distributed.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"In Interviews with Latin American Writers (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000078","text":"When I write, I fly to another dimension. Like Eva Luna, I try to live life as I would like it to be, as in a novel. I am always half flying, like Marc Chagall's violinists.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"In Interviews with Latin American Writers (1989)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000079","text":"Daily life is brimful of fantasy and at the same time books are saturated with reality. I feel that all things float within the realm of the possible. As a reader I let myself be carried away by the enchantment of a story, without worrying too much about its authenticity. As a writer I abandon myself in the same way to the necessity of telling, convinced that if something is not exactly true at this moment, it may be so tomorrow. That's the way I have found it to be in my work.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000080","text":"I visualized the book as a string of beads. Each anecdote, each character, was a separate bead strung on one string. That is why I wanted to close the book where it began, as if one had fastened the clasp of a necklace. I also wanted to show that life goes in a circle, that events are intertwined, and that history repeats itself. There is no beginning and no end.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000081","text":"(About The House of Spirits) All the women in my book are feminists in their fashion; that is, they ask to be free and complete human beings, to be able to fulfill themselves, not to be dependent on men.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000082","text":"I do realize that human beings are the same everywhere; the differences are not so great. This story of the Trueba family could have happened anywhere.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000083","text":"When I left Chile, after the military coup, I lost in one instant my family, my past, my home. I felt like a tree without roots, destined to dry up and die. For many years I was paralyzed by a kind of stupor and by nostalgia, but one day in January of 1981, I decided to recover what I had lost. I sat down to write the story of a family similar to mine, the story of a country that could be mine, a continent resembling Latin America... It was almost the act of a conjurer.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000084","text":"Democratic values have never disappeared from Chile. We must not confuse the Chilean nation with the dictatorship that is ruling it now. Chile is its people, its land, its past, its present, and its future. Pinochet and the evil ones who are with him are an accident in the long life of my country. They will go into history as a misfortune that darkened the sky, but they will go.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-allende-000085","text":"My work as a journalist has been fundamental in my literary creations. Journalism taught me to know and love words, the tools of my trade, the material of my craft. Journalism taught me to search for truth and to try to be objective, how to capture the reader and to hold him firmly and not let him escape. It taught me to synthesize ideas and to be precise about events. And above all, it rid me of any fear of the blank page.","author":"Isabel Allende","source":"in Imagine 1(Winter 1984)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","theme:women","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000001","text":"Ahora tenemos un peronismo que es todo: es la extrema derecha, es el centro, es el centro izquierda, es la extrema izquierda, es la democracia y es el terrorismo, es la demagogia y es la insensatez... Todo es el peronismo...","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-vargas-000002","text":"Political correctness is the enemy of freedom because it rejects honesty and authenticity. We have to tackle it as the distortion of the truth.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"Wikiquote","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Source citation unavailable on Wikiquote page"},{"id":"latin-vargas-000003","text":"It is easy to know what you want to say, but not to say it.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000004","text":"Lima frightened him, it was too big, you could lose yourself in it and never find your way home; the people on the street were total strangers.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000005","text":"He is always furious, on account of what he finds out or what he doesn't find out.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000006","text":"Every thing is done halfway in Peru, and that is why everything goes wrong.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000007","text":"When you start having bad luck, there isn't an end to it.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000008","text":"We all believe in the regulations, but you have to know how to interpret them.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000009","text":"You can't make facts fit the rules, it is the other way round. The rules have to be adopted to fit the facts.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000010","text":"A clean conscience might help you to get into heaven. but it won't help your career.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Time of the Hero (1963)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000011","text":"¿Tienen algo que ver con los intereses de los humildes las querellas retóricas de los partidos burgueses?","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The War at the End of the World (1981)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000012","text":"Reading changed dreams into life and life into dreams.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"Nobel Lecture (2010)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000013","text":"Like writing, reading is a protest against the insufficiencies of life. When we look in fiction for what is missing in life, we are saying, with no need to say it or even to know it, that life as it is does not satisfy our thirst for the absolute – the foundation of the human condition – and should be better. We invent fictions in order to live somehow the many lives we would like to lead when we barely have one at our disposal.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"Nobel Lecture (2010)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000014","text":"Good literature erects bridges between different peoples, and by having us enjoy, suffer, or feel surprise, unites us beneath the languages, beliefs, habits, customs, and prejudices that separate us.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"Nobel Lecture (2010)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000015","text":"Literature creates a fraternity within human diversity and eclipses the frontiers erected among men and women by ignorance, ideologies, religions, languages, and stupidity.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"Nobel Lecture (2010)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000016","text":"[I]t is normal for outsiders to have a better understanding of what is happening inside dictatorial regimes, because censorship prevents those suffering under dictatorship from being fully aware of the situation in which they are living.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Call of the Tribe (2018)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000017","text":"[C]ommon sense is the most valuable of political virtues.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Call of the Tribe (2018)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true},{"id":"latin-vargas-000018","text":"[T]here is literally no bastion of knowledge, not even in the exact sciences, that ideology, with its powers of distortion, cannot breach and into which lies useful to the cause cannot be implanted.","author":"Mario Vargas Llosa","source":"The Call of the Tribe (2018)","tags":["audience:inspiration","audience:morning","language:en","theme:freedom","theme:literature","theme:politics","theme:wisdom","tradition:latinAmerican"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":true}]}